{"title_page": "Macrocystis", "text_new": "{{short description|Genus of large brown algae}}\n{{about||the genus of mushrooms|Macrocystidia|the condition of enlarged red blood cells|Macrocytosis}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Giantkelp2 300.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[Macrocystis pyrifera]]''\n| taxon = Macrocystis\n| synonyms = {{plainlist|\n*''Macrocystis angustifolia''\n*''Macrocystis integrifolia''\n*''Macrocystis laevis''\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Macrocystis''''' is a monospecific genus<ref>E.C. Macaya and G.C. Zuccarello (2010) DNA barcoding and genetic divergence in the Giant Kelp Macrocystis (Laminariales). Journal of Phycology 46(4): 736\u2013742.</ref> of [[kelp]] (large [[brown algae]]). This genus contains the largest of all the [[phaeophyceae]] or [[brown algae]].  ''Macrocystis'' has [[pneumatocyst]]s at the base of its [[blade]]s.  [[Sporophyte]]s are perennial and the individual may live for up to three years;<ref>W.J. North (1971) The biology of giant kelp beds.</ref> stipes/fronds within a whole individual undergo [[senescence]], where each frond may persist for approximately 100 days.<ref>G.E. Rodriguez, A. Rassweiler, D.C. Reed, & S.J. Holbrook (2013) The importance of progressive senescence in the biomass dynamics of giant kelp (''Macrocystis pyrifera''). Ecology, 94(8), 1848-1858.</ref> The genus is found widely in [[subtropical]], temperate, and sub-Antarctic oceans of the Southern Hemisphere (e.g. Chile, New Zealand, Australia, Falkland Islands, Auckland Islands, etc.) and in the northeast Pacific from [[Baja California peninsula|Baja California]] to [[Sitka, Alaska]]. ''Macrocystis'' is often a major component of temperate [[kelp forest]]s.\n\n==Description==\n''Macrocystis'' is a monospecific genus, the sole species is ''M. pyrifera''. Some individuals are so huge that the thallus may grow to up to 60&nbsp;m (200&nbsp;ft).<ref name=\"Hoek 95\">C. van den Hoek, D.G. Mann and H.M. Jahns (1995) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=xuUoiFesSHMC&printsec=frontcover Algae An Introduction to Phycology]''. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge. {{ISBN|0-521-30419-9}}</ref> The stipes arise from a [[holdfast]] and branch three or four times from near the base. Blades develop at irregular intervals along the stipe.<ref name=\"Mondragon and Mondragon 03\">Mondragon, Jennifer and Mondragon, Jeff (2003) ''Seaweeds of the Pacific Coast.'' Sea Challengers, Monterey, California. {{ISBN|0-930118-29-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Abbott 76\">I.A. Abbott and G.J. Hollenberg (1976)  ''Marine Algae of California.'' Stanford University Press, California. {{ISBN|0-8047-0867-3}}</ref> ''M. pyrifera'' grows to over 45&nbsp;m (150&nbsp;ft) long.<ref name=\"Abbott 76\"/><ref>A.B. Cribb (1953) [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?act=view_file&file_id=MF9540001.pdf ''Macrocystis pyrifera'' (L.) Ag. in Tasmanian waters] Australian Journal of Marine and Freshwater Research, Vol 5, issue 1.</ref> The stipes are unbranched and each blade has a gas bladder at its base.<ref name=\"Kain 91\">Kain, J M (1991) ''Cultivation of attached seaweeds'' in Guiry, M D and Blunden, G (1991) ''Seaweed Resources in Europe: Uses and Potential.'' John Wiley and Sons.</ref>\n\n==Life cycle==\nThe macroscopic [[sporophyte]] has many specialized blades growing near the holdfast. These blades bear various [[Sorus|sori]] containing [[Sporangium|sporangia]], which release [[haploid]] [[spores]], which will grow into microscopic female and male [[gametophyte]]s.  These gametophytes, after reaching the appropriate substrata, grow [[Mitosis|mitotically]] to eventually produce gametes.<ref name=\"Graham07\">M.H. Graham, J.A. V\u00e1squez and A.H. Buschmann (2007) Global ecology of the giant kelp ''Macrocystis'': From ecotypes to ecosystems. ''Oceanography and Marine Biology: An Annual Review'' 45: 39-88.</ref>\n\nFemales release their eggs ([[oogonia]]) along with a [[pheromone]], the [[lamoxirene]].<ref>I. Maier, D.G. M\u00fcller, G. Gassman, W. Boland and L. Jaenicke (1987)  Sexual pheromones and related egg secretions in Laminariales (Phaeophyta). ''Zeitschrift Naturforschung Section C Biosciences'' 42: 948\u2013954.</ref><ref>I. Maier, C. Hertweck and W. Boland (2001)  Stereochemical specificity of lamoxirene the sperm-releasing\npheromone in kelp (Laminariales, Phaeophyceae). ''Biological Bulletin (Woods Hole)'' 201: 121\u2013125.</ref>  This compound triggers sperm release by males. The ''Macrocystis'' sperm consists of [[biflagellate]] non-[[Photosynthesis|synthetic]] [[antherozoid]]s, which find their way to the oogonia following the lamoxirene. The egg is then fertilized to form the [[zygote]], which, through mitosis, begins growth.\n\n==Growth==\nJuvenile giant kelp grow directly on the parent female gametophyte, extending one or two primary blades, and beginning a rudimentary holdfast, which will eventually cover the gametophyte completely.  Growth occurs with lengthening of the stipe, and splitting of the blades.  This occurs by means of small tears where the blade meets the stipe, which splits the stipe into two.  Pneumatocysts grow after the first few blade splittings.\n\n==Ecology==\n{{Main article|Kelp forest}}\n''Macrocystis'' typically grow forming extensive beds, large \"floating canopies\", on rocky substrata between the low intertidal.<ref name=\"Abbott 76\"/><ref name=\"Graham07\"/> It was harvested by barges which used large blades to harvest up to 300 tons a day along the coast of [[California]].<ref>Smith, G.M. 1955. ''Cryptogamic Botany.'' Volume 1. Algae and Fungi. McGraw-Hill Book Company, Inc.</ref>\n\n==Species==\nInitially, 17 species were described within the genus ''Macrocystis''.<ref>W.J. North (1971) Review of ''Macrocystis'' biology. In ''Biology of Economic Algae'', I. Akatsuka (ed.). Hague: Academic Publishing, 447\u2013527.</ref> In 1874, Hooker, following blade morphology, put them all under the same taxon, ''Macrocystis pyrifera''.<ref>J.D. Hooker (1874)  ''The Botany of the Antarctic Voyage of'' H.M. Discovery'' Ships ''Erebus and ''Terror''. ''I. Flora Antarctica''. London: Reeve Brothers.</ref> In modern times, the large number of species were re-classified based on the holdfast morphology, which distinguished three species (''M. angustifolia'', ''M. integrifolia'', and ''M. pyrifera'') and on blade morphology, which added a fourth species (''M. laevis'') in 1986.<ref>C.H. Hay (1986) A new species of ''Macrocystis'' C. Ag.  (Phaeophyta) from Marion Island, southern Indian Ocean. ''Phycologia'' 25: 241\u2013252.</ref> In 2009 and 2010, however, two studies that used both morphological<ref>K.W. Demes, M.H. Graham, T.S. Suskiewicz (2009) Phenotypic plasticity reconciles incongruous molecular and morphological taxonomies: the Giant Kelp, ''Macrocystis'' (Laminariales, Phaeophyceae), is a monospecific genus. ''Journal of Phycology'' 45(6): 1266\u20131269.</ref> and molecular<ref>E.C. Macaya and G.C. Zuccarello (2010) DNA barcoding and genetic divergence in the Giant Kelp ''Macrocystis'' (Laminariales). ''Journal of Phycology'' 46(4): 736\u2013742.</ref> assessments demonstrate that ''Macrocystis'' is monospecific (as ''M. pyrifera''), which is currently accepted by the phycological community<ref>[[AlgaeBase]]: [http://www.algaebase.org/search/genus/detail/?genus_id=35715 Genus: Macrocystis]</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n''Macrocystis'' is distributed along the eastern Pacific coast from Alaska to Mexico and from Peru and along the [[Argentine|Argentinian]] coast as well as in Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and most sub-Antarctic islands to 60\u00b0S.<ref name=\"Graham07\"/>\n\nAlthough ''Macrocystis'' is a monospecific genus, some split ''M. pyrifera'' into the four morphs, or sub-species, described below:\n\n* ''Macrocystis pyrifera'', known as '''giant kelp''', most widely distributed ''Macrocystis'' species,<ref>M. Neushul (1971) The biology of giant kelp beds (''Macrocystis'') in\nCalifornia: the species of ''Macrocystis''. ''Nova Hedwigia'' 32: 211\u201322.</ref> found in intermediate-to-deep water<ref name=\"Graham07\"/> of [[North America]] ([[Alaska]] to [[California]]), [[South America]], [[South Africa]], [[New Zealand]], and southern [[Australia]].<ref>[[AlgaeBase]]: [http://www.algaebase.org/search/species/detail/?species_id=4427 Species: Macrocystis pyrifera]</ref>\n* ''Macrocystis integrifolia'', typically found on intertidal rocks or shallow subtidal rocks of British Columbia, Mexico, Peru and Northern Chile.<ref name=\"Abbott 76\"/><ref name=\"Graham07\"/><ref>[[AlgaeBase]]: [http://www.algaebase.org/search/species/detail/?species_id=4882&sk=0&from=results Species: Macrocystis integrifolia]</ref>\n* ''Macrocystis laevis'', a smaller, intertidal species, is found on the [[Pacific]] coast of [[North America]] ([[British Columbia]] to [[California]]) and South America.<ref name=\"Abbott 76\"/>\n* ''Macrocystis angustifolia'' Bory, found in shallow waters of South Africa and South Australia.<ref name=\"Graham07\"/><ref name=\"Huisman 00\">J.M. Huisman (2000) ''Marine Plants of Australia.'' University of Western Australia Press. {{ISBN|1-876268-33-6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Lopez, James. \"''Macrocystis pyrifera''.\" Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute. 2001. Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute. 10 Jan 2007\n*M.H. Graham, J.A. V\u00e1squez and A.H. Buschmann (2007) Global ecology of the giant kelp ''Macrocystis'': From ecotypes to ecosystems. ''Oceanography and Marine Biology: An Annual Review'' 45: 39-88.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151017151510/http://www.mbari.org/staff/conn/botany/browns/james/default.htm ''Macrocystis pyrifa'']\n* [http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/guide/brown61.html ''Macrocystis integrifolia'']\n* Bushing, William W (2000) [http://www.starthrower.org/research/kelpmisc/kelp_mp.htm ''Giant Bladder Kelp '']. Retrieved 21 September 2008.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2304985}}\n\n[[Category:Laminariaceae]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Pacific]]\n[[Category:Marine biota of North America]]\n[[Category:Flora of California]]\n[[Category:Flora of the West Coast of the United States]]\n[[Category:Laminariales genera]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genus of large brown algae}}\n{{about||the genus of mushrooms|Macrocystidia|the condition of enlarged red blood cells|Macrocytosis}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Giantkelp2 300.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[Macrocystis pyrifera]]''\n| taxon = Macrocystis\n| synonyms = {{plainlist|\n*''Macrocystis angustifolia''\n*''Macrocystis integrifolia''\n*''Macrocystis laevis''\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Macrocystis''''' is a monospecific genus<ref>E.C. Macaya and G.C. Zuccarello (2010) DNA barcoding and genetic divergence in the Giant Kelp Macrocystis (Laminariales). Journal of Phycology 46(4): 736\u2013742.</ref> of [[kelp]] (large [[brown algae]]). This genus contains the largest of all the [[phaeophyceae]] or [[brown algae]].  ''Macrocystis'' has [[pneumatocyst]]s at the base of its [[blade]]s.  [[Sporophyte]]s are perennial and the individual may live for up to three years;<ref>W.J. North (1971) The biology of giant kelp beds.</ref> stipes/fronds within a whole individual undergo [[senescence]], where each frond may persist for approximately 100 days.<ref>G.E. Rodriguez, A. Rassweiler, D.C. Reed, & S.J. Holbrook (2013) The importance of progressive senescence in the biomass dynamics of giant kelp (''Macrocystis pyrifera''). Ecology, 94(8), 1848-1858.</ref> The genus is found widely in [[subtropical]], temperate, and sub-Antarctic oceans of the Southern Hemisphere (e.g. Chile, New Zealand, Australia, Falkland Islands, Auckland Islands, etc.) and in the northeast Pacific from [[Baja California peninsula|Baja California]] to [[Sitka, Alaska]]. ''Macrocystis'' is often a major component of temperate [[kelp forest]]s.\n\n==Description==\n''Macrocystis'' is a monospecific genus, the sole species is ''M. pyrifera''. Some individuals are so huge that the thallus may grow to up to 60&nbsp;m (200&nbsp;ft).<ref name=\"Hoek 95\">C. van den Hoek, D.G. Mann and H.M. Jahns (1995) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=xuUoiFesSHMC&printsec=frontcover Algae An Introduction to Phycology]''. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge. {{ISBN|0-521-30419-9}}</ref> The stipes arise from a [[holdfast]] and branch three or four times from near the base. Blades develop at irregular intervals along the stipe.<ref name=\"Mondragon and Mondragon 03\">Mondragon, Jennifer and Mondragon, Jeff (2003) ''Seaweeds of the Pacific Coast.'' Sea Challengers, Monterey, California. {{ISBN|0-930118-29-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Abbott 76\">I.A. Abbott and G.J. Hollenberg (1976)  ''Marine Algae of California.'' Stanford University Press, California. {{ISBN|0-8047-0867-3}}</ref> ''M. pyrifera'' grows to over 45&nbsp;m (150&nbsp;ft) long.<ref name=\"Abbott 76\"/><ref>A.B. Cribb (1953) [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?act=view_file&file_id=MF9540001.pdf ''Macrocystis pyrifera'' (L.) Ag. in Tasmanian waters] Australian Journal of Marine and Freshwater Research, Vol 5, issue 1.</ref> The stipes are unbranched and each blade has a gas bladder at its base.<ref name=\"Kain 91\">Kain, J M (1991) ''Cultivation of attached seaweeds'' in Guiry, M D and Blunden, G (1991) ''Seaweed Resources in Europe: Uses and Potential.'' John Wiley and Sons.</ref>\n\n==Life cycle==\nThe macroscopic [[sporophyte]] has many specialized blades growing near the holdfast. These blades bear various [[Sorus|sori]] containing [[Sporangium|sporangia]], which release [[haploid]] [[spores]], which will grow into microscopic female and male [[gametophyte]]s.  These gametophytes, after reaching the appropriate substrata, grow [[Mitosis|mitotically]] to eventually produce gametes.<ref name=\"Graham07\">M.H. Graham, J.A. V\u00e1squez and A.H. Buschmann (2007) Global ecology of the giant kelp ''Macrocystis'': From ecotypes to ecosystems. ''Oceanography and Marine Biology: An Annual Review'' 45: 39-88.</ref>\n\nFemales release their eggs ([[oogonia]]) along with a [[pheromone]], the lamoxirene.<ref>I. Maier, D.G. M\u00fcller, G. Gassman, W. Boland and L. Jaenicke (1987)  Sexual pheromones and related egg secretions in Laminariales (Phaeophyta). ''Zeitschrift Naturforschung Section C Biosciences'' 42: 948\u2013954.</ref><ref>I. Maier, C. Hertweck and W. Boland (2001)  Stereochemical specificity of lamoxirene the sperm-releasing\npheromone in kelp (Laminariales, Phaeophyceae). ''Biological Bulletin (Woods Hole)'' 201: 121\u2013125.</ref>  This compound triggers sperm release by males. The ''Macrocystis'' sperm consists of [[biflagellate]] non-[[Photosynthesis|synthetic]] [[antherozoid]]s, which find their way to the oogonia following the lamoxirene. The egg is then fertilized to form the [[zygote]], which, through mitosis, begins growth.\n\n==Growth==\nJuvenile giant kelp grow directly on the parent female gametophyte, extending one or two primary blades, and beginning a rudimentary holdfast, which will eventually cover the gametophyte completely.  Growth occurs with lengthening of the stipe, and splitting of the blades.  This occurs by means of small tears where the blade meets the stipe, which splits the stipe into two.  Pneumatocysts grow after the first few blade splittings.\n\n==Ecology==\n{{Main article|Kelp forest}}\n''Macrocystis'' typically grow forming extensive beds, large \"floating canopies\", on rocky substrata between the low intertidal.<ref name=\"Abbott 76\"/><ref name=\"Graham07\"/> It was harvested by barges which used large blades to harvest up to 300 tons a day along the coast of [[California]].<ref>Smith, G.M. 1955. ''Cryptogamic Botany.'' Volume 1. Algae and Fungi. McGraw-Hill Book Company, Inc.</ref>\n\n==Species==\nInitially, 17 species were described within the genus ''Macrocystis''.<ref>W.J. North (1971) Review of ''Macrocystis'' biology. In ''Biology of Economic Algae'', I. Akatsuka (ed.). Hague: Academic Publishing, 447\u2013527.</ref> In 1874, Hooker, following blade morphology, put them all under the same taxon, ''Macrocystis pyrifera''.<ref>J.D. Hooker (1874)  ''The Botany of the Antarctic Voyage of'' H.M. Discovery'' Ships ''Erebus and ''Terror''. ''I. Flora Antarctica''. London: Reeve Brothers.</ref> In modern times, the large number of species were re-classified based on the holdfast morphology, which distinguished three species (''M. angustifolia'', ''M. integrifolia'', and ''M. pyrifera'') and on blade morphology, which added a fourth species (''M. laevis'') in 1986.<ref>C.H. Hay (1986) A new species of ''Macrocystis'' C. Ag.  (Phaeophyta) from Marion Island, southern Indian Ocean. ''Phycologia'' 25: 241\u2013252.</ref> In 2009 and 2010, however, two studies that used both morphological<ref>K.W. Demes, M.H. Graham, T.S. Suskiewicz (2009) Phenotypic plasticity reconciles incongruous molecular and morphological taxonomies: the Giant Kelp, ''Macrocystis'' (Laminariales, Phaeophyceae), is a monospecific genus. ''Journal of Phycology'' 45(6): 1266\u20131269.</ref> and molecular<ref>E.C. Macaya and G.C. Zuccarello (2010) DNA barcoding and genetic divergence in the Giant Kelp ''Macrocystis'' (Laminariales). ''Journal of Phycology'' 46(4): 736\u2013742.</ref> assessments demonstrate that ''Macrocystis'' is monospecific (as ''M. pyrifera''), which is currently accepted by the phycological community<ref>[[AlgaeBase]]: [http://www.algaebase.org/search/genus/detail/?genus_id=35715 Genus: Macrocystis]</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n''Macrocystis'' is distributed along the eastern Pacific coast from Alaska to Mexico and from Peru and along the [[Argentine|Argentinian]] coast as well as in Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and most sub-Antarctic islands to 60\u00b0S.<ref name=\"Graham07\"/>\n\nAlthough ''Macrocystis'' is a monospecific genus, some split ''M. pyrifera'' into the four morphs, or sub-species, described below:\n\n* ''Macrocystis pyrifera'', known as '''giant kelp''', most widely distributed ''Macrocystis'' species,<ref>M. Neushul (1971) The biology of giant kelp beds (''Macrocystis'') in\nCalifornia: the species of ''Macrocystis''. ''Nova Hedwigia'' 32: 211\u201322.</ref> found in intermediate-to-deep water<ref name=\"Graham07\"/> of [[North America]] ([[Alaska]] to [[California]]), [[South America]], [[South Africa]], [[New Zealand]], and southern [[Australia]].<ref>[[AlgaeBase]]: [http://www.algaebase.org/search/species/detail/?species_id=4427 Species: Macrocystis pyrifera]</ref>\n* ''Macrocystis integrifolia'', typically found on intertidal rocks or shallow subtidal rocks of British Columbia, Mexico, Peru and Northern Chile.<ref name=\"Abbott 76\"/><ref name=\"Graham07\"/><ref>[[AlgaeBase]]: [http://www.algaebase.org/search/species/detail/?species_id=4882&sk=0&from=results Species: Macrocystis integrifolia]</ref>\n* ''Macrocystis laevis'', a smaller, intertidal species, is found on the [[Pacific]] coast of [[North America]] ([[British Columbia]] to [[California]]) and South America.<ref name=\"Abbott 76\"/>\n* ''Macrocystis angustifolia'' Bory, found in shallow waters of South Africa and South Australia.<ref name=\"Graham07\"/><ref name=\"Huisman 00\">J.M. Huisman (2000) ''Marine Plants of Australia.'' University of Western Australia Press. {{ISBN|1-876268-33-6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Lopez, James. \"''Macrocystis pyrifera''.\" Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute. 2001. Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute. 10 Jan 2007\n*M.H. Graham, J.A. V\u00e1squez and A.H. Buschmann (2007) Global ecology of the giant kelp ''Macrocystis'': From ecotypes to ecosystems. ''Oceanography and Marine Biology: An Annual Review'' 45: 39-88.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151017151510/http://www.mbari.org/staff/conn/botany/browns/james/default.htm ''Macrocystis pyrifa'']\n* [http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/guide/brown61.html ''Macrocystis integrifolia'']\n* Bushing, William W (2000) [http://www.starthrower.org/research/kelpmisc/kelp_