{"title_page": "Walkerville Brewery", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n'''Walkerville Brewery''' was a brewer of beer in [[Adelaide]], South Australia. The company became a Co-operative, and grew by admitting hotel owners as shareholders, and absorbed smaller breweries. After several amalgamations it moved its operations to Southwark (now part of [[Thebarton, South Australia|Thebarton]]) and by 1920 it was South Australia's largest brewing company. It was bought out by the [[South Australian Brewing Company]] in 1939<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article35591554 |title=Big Brewery Deal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=25 June 1938 |accessdate=9 February 2018 |page=26 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and its facilities became the company's Southwark brewery, which still operates.\n\n==History==\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord = {{coord|-34.8958| 138.6175}} <!--latitude and longitude as a +/- decimal.-->\n| zoom = 16 <!--(1=whole world, 18=a street)-->\n| width = 300\n| height = 350\n| shape1=n-square\n| shape-color1=blue\n| shape-outline1=white\n| mark-coord1 = {{coord|-34.894 | 138.6182}}\n| mark-title1 = Walkerville Brewery Lots 66, 67\n| mark-coord2 = {{coord|-34.8958 | 138.6171}}\n| mark-title2 = Lot 41 Walkerville\n| caption = Walkerville Tce is highlighted yellow. The section beyond Fuller Street is not seen on early maps.\n| auto-caption=1\n}}\n\nThe first brewery in Walkerville was founded by William Colyer and William Williams, South Australia's first licensed publican.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article159532901 |title=Licensed Victuallers' Society |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=VIII |issue=351 |location=South Australia |date=16 March 1850 |accessdate=25 February 2018 |page=2 (Supplement to the \"Adelaide Observer\") |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The partnership was dissolved late the same year, Colyer returned to England.,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158919398 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |issue=74 |location=South Australia |date=23 November 1844 |accessdate=24 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nWilliams embarked on a program of expansion. He commissioned architect Thomas Price<ref>Price was active in Adelaide 1845\u201350; laid out the suburb Knightsbridge (became part of [[Leabrook, South Australia|Leabrook]]), designed New Queen's Theatre for [[George Coppin]], a housing estate for [[Bean Brothers|George Bean]], grandstand at the [[Old Adelaide Racecourse]] and did much dealing in real estate.</ref> to erect new buildings on Fuller Street in 1846,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71606683 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The South Australian]] |volume=IX |issue=792 |location=South Australia |date=11 December 1846 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> identified as Lots 66 and 67,<ref name=Lewis/> although Lots 64 and 65 on the other side of Walkerville Terrace (also known as Richmond Road) closer to the Torrens would seem more likely.\nA series of tunnels running down to the [[River Torrens|Torrens]] from Fuller Street and Warwick Street served as cellars (filled in c. 1970 preparatory to erecting the Highways Department building).<ref name=Scales>{{cite book|title=John Walker's Village|author=Marjorie Scales|publisher=Rigby Ltd, Adelaide|year=1974|isbn=0851798292}}</ref> The \"tunnel\" story has elsewhere been debunked, and identified as nothing but drains.<ref name=Lewis/> \nWilliams was found insolvent 1851, but had his certificate annulled in 1853.\nAt some stage there was another brewery on Lot 41, Walkerville, on land purchased by N. P. Levi in October 1842,<ref name=Lewis>{{cite book|title=The Walkerville Story: 140 years|author=John Lewis|publisher=The Corporation of the Town of Walkerville|year=1988|isbn=073163067X}}</ref> but whether part of this history is as yet not determined.\n*William Williams (c. 1803 \u2013 26 April 1858),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207161191 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[Adelaide Times]] |volume=XII |issue=2297 |location=South Australia |date=28 April 1858 |accessdate=25 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> arrived 1836 aboard {{ship||Africaine|1832 ship|2}}<ref>Not to be confused with William Williams (c. 1817 \u2013 17 August 1859), also on the \"[[First Fleet of South Australia]]\" aboard ''Cygnet'', married Maria Wickham (1820 \u2013 17 February 1872), https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/92270959 with parents aboard ''Africaine'', on 12 August 1839</ref> and was \"the first (colonist) to drink Torrens water\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38441302 |title=The Old Colonists' Festival |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XV |issue=1360 |location=South Australia |date=22 February 1851 |accessdate=1 March 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He married Jane Catchlove (c. 1811 \u2013 20 April 1885) on 2 July 1837. Jane arrived in South Australia in November 1836 aboard {{ship||Tam O'Shanter|ship|2}} with her father Edward William Catchlove and three brothers and sisters. Henry Catchlove of [[Hindmarsh Brewery]] was an uncle. William and Jane had seven children, among them William Huey Williams MD was educated at [[Adelaide Educational Institution|AEI]] and [[St Peter's College, Adelaide|SPC]], appointed  Resident House Physician, Royal infirmary Liverpool; and Mary Laura Williams (1845 \u2013 13 November 1880) married Thomas Moseley, son of [[Henry Jackson Moseley|Henry Moseley]] of Glenelg, on 25 October 1877.\n:Williams gained notoriety in 1851 for his obstruction to the formation of the Walkerville Anglican Church committee.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207066507 |title=Walkerville Church Case |newspaper=[[Adelaide Times]] |volume=II |issue=360 |location=South Australia |date=20 January 1851 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> \n:He died destitute and a subscription organised to benefit his widow and seven children<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49772847 |title=Provision for the Widow |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XXII |issue=3629 |location=South Australia |date=25 May 1858 |accessdate=1 March 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> was well patronised.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158125140 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=XVI |issue=869 |location=South Australia |date=29 May 1858 |accessdate=1 March 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n<!--only two found in GDB: Mary Laura 1845 and Frederich 1847; no mention of Mary Williams (c. 1848 \u2013 14 October 1919) who married George Moseley (1850\u2013 ) on 25 November 1875.-->\nEdmund Levi, brother of Philip, the property's owner, took over management of Walkerville Brewery in 1853,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39813610 |title=Insolvency Court |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XXXIX |issue=8607 |location=South Australia |date=17 June 1874 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> leasing it to one James Thomson.\nIn January 1860 fire destroyed the malthouse, which had been leased to Richard Goss<!--father of William, Frances, Francis--> (died 1869), who sold malt to Simms as well as to Thomson. In 1854 Thomson relinquished his share of the business<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48552610 |title=Notice to Innkeepers: Walkerville Brewery |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XVIII |issue=2354 |location=South Australia |date=2 April 1854 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and in October left the partnership to White & Phillips<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49201658 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XIII |issue=2529 |location=South Australia |date=30 October 1854 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> who shortly went bankrupt.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49765148 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XXI |issue=3289 |location=South Australia |date=21 April 1857 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}} Samuel Vincent Price Phillips,</ref> Thomson was found insolvent in 1864 and jailed for two months.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article159527679 |title=Law and Criminal Courts - Insolvency Court. |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=XXII |issue=1209 |location=South Australia |date=3 December 1864 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He was not clearly related to [[James Turnbull Thomson]], brewer and founder of [[Balhannah, South Australia|Balhannnah]], who had more than his share of financial failures.\n*William Hardyman Colyer (17 January 1816 \u2013 15 August 1891 in [[Rondebosch]]) arrived in South Australia aboard ''Winchester'' September 1838, and acted as brewer for a company in Launceston<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66022313 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Cornwall Chronicle]] |volume=9 |issue=468 |location=Tasmania, Australia |date=11 November 1843 |accessdate=24 February 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> before in 1844 founding a brewery in [[Walkerville, South Australia]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27446662 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=South Australia |date=28 February 1844 |accessdate=25 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}It is likely he acted as consultant, setting up a brewery, training a successor and moving on.</ref> He later settled in [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southafricansettlers.com/?p=21462|title=South African Settlers: William Hardyman Colyer|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref> \n*Edmund Levi (1827 \u2013 30 July 1895) arrived in Adelaide in 1842, joined brother Philip's P. Levi & Co. in 1854. He married Gertrude Goldsmid in 1862.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article34518082 |title=Death of Mr. Edmund Levi |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XXXVIII |issue=11478 |location=South Australia |date=1 August 1895 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Charles White ( \u2013 ) <!--perhaps (c. 1834 \u2013 5 June 1917)--> was chairman of the first Council of the District of Walkerville, with councillors J. H. Swann, John Campbell, J. D. Woods, and Thomas Beadle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article129738886 |title=Municipal Fathers |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)]] |volume=VII |issue=958 |location=South Australia |date=9 August 1926 |accessdate=24 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}List of Walkerville Council chairmen</ref>\n*Samuel Vincent Price <!--Price in SA, Pryce everywhere else--> Phillips ( \u2013 c. 1896) left for the goldfields c. 1858, died in England.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article190611549 |title=Probate and Administration |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=12,899 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=3 July 1896 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*James Thomson was perhaps James Thomson \"the elder\" who arrived aboard ''Moffat'' December 1839 with wife Mary (c. 1791 \u2013 5 April 1875), with children Emma and Thomas, founded Sussex Arms Hotel 1843, died before 1875. In 1847 his daughter Betsy Thomson (c. 1816 \u2013 12 February 1893) married James Maskall Nottage (1821 \u2013 17 December 1879),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71607508 |title=Local News. |newspaper=[[The South Australian]] |volume=X |issue=817 |location=South Australia |date=9 March 1847 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> to whom Thomson transferred the \"Sussex Arms\"' licence in 1853, and for whom Nottage Terrace was named.<ref name=district>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article64316447 |title=Walkerville, Medindie and District |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)]] |volume=LXXXVIII |issue=25,774 |location=South Australia |date=6 August 1923 |accessdate=14 February 2018 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}} Daughter Louisa Thomson married Benjamin Boyce ( \u2013 1 December 1847), subject of [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/boyce-benjamin-12813 ADB article], on 26 September 1843</ref>\n\nAround 1862 Ball & Huntley took over Thomson's defunct brewery, named it the \"Black Horse Brewery\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Hallett Shuehard and David Tuckwell|title=Brewers and aerated Water Manufacturers in South Australia 1836\u20131936|isbn=0-646-14678-5|year=1992}}</ref><ref name=Walkerville>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26756621 |title=The Walkerville Brewery |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XXXIII |issue=9899 |location=South Australia |date=10 July 1890 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and began brewing there again, purchasing the property in 1870.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39175006 |title=The Breweries of Adelaide and Its Suburbs |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XXXII |issue=6729 |location=South Australia |date=1 June 1868 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nTheir malthouse was destroyed by fire on 5 June 1871. Ball died in 1882 and Huntley continued operating the brewery until 1890<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5547777 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=LX |issue=18,369 |location=South Australia |date=28 August 1917 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> when he retired.\n\n*George Ball (c. 1831 \u2013 1 November 1882) and his wife Anna Jane Ball (c. 1834 \u2013 4 June 1924) arrived in Adelaide aboard emigrant ship ''China'' in November 1852.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57389926 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)]] |volume=LXXXIX |issue=26,035 |location=South Australia |date=6 June 1924 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*George Huntley (5 February 1832 \u2013 9 August 1917) arrived in Adelaide around 1851,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5547777 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=LX |issue=18,369 |location=South Australia |date=28 August 1917 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> worked as a builder, then for White & Phillips, brewers. In September 1855 he married Mary Ann Clarke, widow of Joseph Clarke of Walkerville.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article164135062 |title=Mr. George Huntley. |newspaper=[[The Observer (Adelaide)]] |volume=LXXIV |issue=5,661 |location=South Australia |date=1 September 1917 |accessdate=14 February 2018 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}} Joseph and Mary Ann Clarke arrived aboard Harpley, perhaps refugees from France, in September 1848. Joseph's death was not reported in newspapers or in BMD lists, perhaps interstate.</ref>\n\nIn 1889 the brewery was taken over and run as a co-operative by a consortium of four \"free\" hotel owners: Robert Hyman, John Selby Cocker, Samuel Harris, and Vincent Henry Simpson.<ref name=Walkerville/>\n*Robert Hyman (1851 \u2013 December 1903), a Finnish-born hotelkeeper, was a founder of Walkerville Brewery Co-operative in 1889 and remained one of the largest shareholders m that business and on board of directors from 1886 to 1903.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article163039401 |title=Oituary |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=LX |issue=3,247 |location=South Australia |date=26 December 1903 |accessdate=8 February 2018 |page=31 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He married Sarah North in 1876; a granddaughter Gwendoline Kathleen Hyman (1903\u20131992) on 16 February 1926) married [[Alfred von Doussa|Louis Alfred von Doussa]] in 1926\n*John Selby Cocker (c. 1844 \u2013 14 April 1901) arrived with his father aboard ''Hooghly'' in October 1846, worked on the [[Australian Overland Telegraph Line|Overland Telegraph Line]], then as a baker before taking over his father's Kentish Arms Hotel on Stanley Street, North Adelaide. He was one of the four original members of the Co-operative. He married Joan Agnes Dineen in 1878.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4833385 |title=The Late Mr. J. S. Cocker |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XLIII |issue=13,262 |location=South Australia |date=20 April 1901 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Samuel Harris (c. 1844 \u2013 23 February 1904) arrived in South Australia with his parents aboard ''John Bunyan'' in 1854. After many years with the coachmaking firm of Barlow & Sons he became landlord, then publican of the Gasworks Hotel in Brompton. He was chairman of directors of the Walkerville Co-operative for ten years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4947254 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XLVI |issue=14,150 |location=South Australia |date=24 February 1904 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Vincent Henry Simpson (1860 \u2013 12 July 1926) was born in Norwood a son of Frederick John Simpson (died 1883), and educated at Unwin's school in North Adelaide. He was publican of the Buckingham Arms, Gilberton at an early age, and married Emily Chittleborough (  \u20131952) in 1885. He was chairman of directors of the Co-operative.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46529483 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=14 July 1926 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe Walkerville Brewing Company was founded with 19 other shareholders, all publicans or hotel owners, whose share of the profits depended on the amount of trade they did with the company.\n\nThe company merged with Clark and Ware's company and its operations moved to Southwark, but the Walkerville Brewery had one last spasm when it was resurrected by Charles Williams in 1901 and operated for five more years before closing for the last time; see below for more information.\n\n==Amalgamations==\n;Torrenside Brewery\nFrequently spelled \"Torrensside\", the brewery was founded by the [[Port Road, Adelaide|Port Road]] Southwark, now [[Thebarton, South Australia|Thebarton]], on the banks of the Torrens in 1886 by A. W. & T. L. Ware. Their first customer was the Exchange Hotel, operated by their brothers George and Boxer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36328197 |title=The Torrenside Brewery |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |volume=XXVIII |issue=8600 |location=South Australia |date=12 May 1886 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe Ware brothers were sons of Charles James Ware (c. 1824 \u2013 19 December 1891) who arrived in SA aboard ''Augustus'' in November 1846 and married Fanny Crawford (1829 \u2013 7 April 1898) on 22 August 1859. Fanny arrived with her parents aboard ''D'Auvergne'' in March 1839. Fanny was the daughter of William Crawford, Builder. Charles ran the Burra Hotel, then in 1868 took over the Exchange Hotel, owned by Sir [[Henry Ayers]]. \n*Arthur Wellington Ware CMG (1861 \u2013 29 January 1927) Mayor of Adelaide 1898\u20131901. He married Rosa Henrietta Haussen (2 November 1860 \u2013 29 November 1915) of the [[Hindmarsh Brewery]] Haussen family, on 11 March 1884.\n*Thomas Lincoln \"Tom\" Ware (1864 \u2013 22 December 1896) died while swimming near the [[Grange, South Australia|Grange]] jetty.\n*George James Ware (15 February 1867 \u2013 17 June 1948) \n*(Charles) Boxer Ware (26 December 1870 \u2013 23 July 1932) was educated at [[Stanley Grammar School]], [[Watervale, South Australia|Watervale]], served as mayor of [[City of West Torrens|Thebarton]] for four years and for some time chairman of directors, Walkerville Co-operative Brewing.\n\n;East Adelaide Brewery\nEdward Clark, son of [[W. H. Clark (brewer)|W. H. Clark]], was brewer for the Murray Brewery in [[Goolwa, South Australia|Goolwa]] in the 1880s, formed E. Clark & Co. in Adelaide with one A. Wheelwright, was found insolvent in 1889 through lack of capital, then served as brewer for the Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company. He left the Co-operative in 1895 to manage the East Adelaide Brewery, a two-storey establishment which the newly revived E. Clark & Co. built on the south side of the River Torrens, on Walkerville Road (now Stephen Terrace).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article166458866 |title=The East Adelaide Brewery |newspaper=[[Quiz And The Lantern]] |volume=IX |issue=422 |location=South Australia |date=23 September 1897 |accessdate=27 February 2018 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The probable location is about 1{{nbsp}}km south of the Walkerville Brewery.\n\nE. Clark & Co. was founded with twelve shareholders inc. William Warren, James Wells, and Eliza Dreyer<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article165619439 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Observer (Adelaide)]] |volume=LXXXIII |issue=7,037 |location=South Australia |date=2 October 1926 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> as Clark & Co., became Clark, Ware & Co. before absorbing the old Walkerville Brewing Company.\n* William Walter Warren (c. 1860 \u2013 24 February 1938) may have had a hotel, but was better known as a racehorse breeder.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131906564 |title=Mr. W. Warren Dead: Saw 54 Melbourne Cups |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)]] |volume=XXX |issue=4,553 |location=South Australia |date=25 February 1938 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*James Samuel Wells (1872\u20131959), son of Michael Wells ( \u2013 14 August 1887) and Elizabeth Wells n\u00e9e Davis ( \u2013 ), owners of Parkside Hotel.\n*Eliza Jane Dreyer (c. 1861 \u2013 25 September 1926) had Prince Albert Hotel in Wright street for 30 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54872728 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)]] |volume=XCI |issue=26,555 |location=South Australia |date=27 September 1926 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nThe product proved so popular the factory's capacity had to be doubled a year later. In 1897 a bottling plant was installed and production capacity doubled again. By 1898 the East Adelaide Brewery was contracted to supply fifty \"free houses\", and once again a doubling of capacity was deemed necessary to keep up with demand.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54543933 |title=Amalgamation of Two Breweries |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=LXIII |issue=16,039 |location=South Australia |date=9 April 1898 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nIt was decided instead to amalgamate with the Wares' Torrenside Brewery, which took place in April 1898, their owners combining as Clark, Ware & Co.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article209134789 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Express and Telegraph]] |volume=XXXV |issue=10,336 |location=South Australia |date=9 April 1898 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}.</ref>\nThe East Adelaide premises were closed and the Torrenside brewery at Southwark expanded.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article29402231 |title=Enterprising Brewers |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=9 April 1898 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;Walkerville Co-operative\nIn 1899 the activities of the Walkerville Brewing Company and Clark, Ware & Co. combined as Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company at Southwark. Additional buildings were erected at the site.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54852723 |title=Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=LXIV |issue=16,548 |location=South Australia |date=25 November 1899 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nThe old Walkerville Brewery was taken over by its erstwhile head brewer Charles Williams in 1901<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4848269 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XLIV |issue=13,340 |location=South Australia |date=20 July 1901 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and operated successfully as \"Williams' Walkerville Brewery\", with outlets at the Tea Tree Gully Hotel<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article166341746 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[Quiz (Adelaide newspaper)]] |volume=XVII |issue=870 |location=South Australia |date=1 June 1906 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and perhaps a few others not tied to either of the two combines, no doubt to the chagrin of the Co-operative, which bought out the company in 1906.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5085148 |title=A Brewery Combine |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |volume=XLVIII |issue=14,881 |location=South Australia |date=28 June 1906 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*[[Samuel Joshua Jacobs]] (1853 \u2013 1937) was chairman of directors from the formation of the Company, succeeded by C. Boxer Ware. He was also president of Chamber of Commerce, and of United Chambers of Manufacture, chairman of [[Adelaide Tattersalls Club|Tattersalls Racing Club]].\n*Charles Williams (c. 1850 \u2013 c. 12 April 1936) was born in Adelaide, educated at [[J. L. Young]]'s [[Adelaide Educational Institution]], worked at the brewery his father John Williams (c. 1806 \u2013 29 June 1876) owned at [[Angas Park, South Australia|Angas Park]], then in [[Ballarat]]. He became head brewer at the [[Lion Brewing and Malting Company]] and for the Walkerville Brewing Company. When that company moved to Southwark he reopened the old facility and continued brewing for another five years. After ten years' inactivity he became brewer for the [[Waverley Brewery]], Mitcham and retired at the age of 83.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74156283 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=18 April 1936 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=21 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Relationship, if any, to William Williams, Adelaide's first publican and founder of Walkerville Brewery has not been determined.\nA popular drink produced by the Walkerville Co-op was K\u00f6nig Lager, whose name was changed to Adelaide Lager in 1914 amid the anti-German sentiment that swept Australia and resulted in wholesale [[List of Australian place names changed from German names|changing of German-sounding place names]].\nThe Walkerville Co-Operative Brewing Co. continued its growth and by the end of World War I was the largest brewery in South Australia.\n\nIn September 1925 Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company, Limited, was first listed on the Adelaide Stock Exchange. Directors were Charles Boxer Ware, Frederick James Blades, Vincent Henry Simpson, and William Walter Warren.\n\nThe company absorbed [[Hindmarsh Brewery|Haussen's Brewery]] in 1926; Haussen & Co. retained ownership of its string of hotels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54823647 |title=Walkerville Brewery Development |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)]] |volume=XCI |issue=26,598 |location=South Australia |date=16 November 1926 |accessdate=9 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1925 the Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company Ltd signed an agreement with the Nathan Institute of Z\u01d4rich for the installation of a \"Nathan patent\" plant at the company's brewery at Southwark, and has been claimed as the first Australian adopter of the system. It was a major project for the brewery, requiring the erection of additional buildings to accommodate the new equipment. Beer production commenced in the Nathan plant late in 1927, and a formal opening ceremony was held in January 1928. However Nathan's process was in operation at [[Peter Grant Hay]]'s Richmond N.S. Brewery in 1927, so although they signed the contract earlier, Southwark brewery was the second in Australia to implement the system.\n*[[Leopold Nathan]], born 30 July 1864 in [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg|W\u00fcrttemberg]], Germany, invented a closed brewing system in [[cylindro-conical]] vessels, which he began marketing in the 1920s. His system removed many of the uncertainties in the brewing process, ensuring a reliable, consistent, high quality product.\n\nThe company made substantial losses in the year 1928\u201329.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article215997590 |title=The Liquor Trades and Licensed Victuallers' World |newspaper=[[The Sport (Adelaide newspaper)]] |volume=XIX |issue=998 |location=South Australia |date=7 November 1929 |accessdate=9 February 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;South Australian Brewing Company\nThe Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company Ltd. was bought out by the [[South Australian Brewing Company]] in 1939 and its facilities became the company's main brewery, which still operates at the same location, and in 1949 was renamed from Walkerville brewery to Southwark Brewery.\n\nWalkerville Nathan beer was renamed Southwark beer in November 1951.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130913474 |title=Nathan Beer Renamed: \"Same Brew\" |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)]] |volume=57 |issue=8,818 |location=South Australia |date=12 November 1951 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beeradelaide.com/blog.php?ID=10048|title=Beer Adelaide: Southwark Bitter|access-date=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\nAn article on the practicalities of beer brewing in Adelaide ([[West End Brewery|West End]], [[Kent Town Brewery|Kent Town]], [[Union Brewery (Adelaide)|Union]], [[Pirie Street Brewery|Pirie Street]], [[Hindmarsh Brewery|Hindmarsh]], [[Morphett Street Brewery|Morphett Street]], and Walkerville breweries) in the late 1860s may be read [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/39175006 here].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1844 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:1927 disestablishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Beer brewing companies based in South Australia]]\n[[Category:Breweries in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n'''Walkerville Brewery''' was a brewer of beer in [[Adelaide]], South Australia. The company became a Co-operative, and grew by admitting hotel owners as shareholders, and absorbed smaller breweries. After several amalgamations it moved its operations to Southwark (now part of [[Thebarton, South Australia|Thebarton]]) and by 1920 it was South Australia's largest brewing company. It was bought out by the [[South Australian Brewing Company]] in 1939<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article35591554 |title=Big Brewery Deal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=25 June 1938 |accessdate=9 February 2018 |page=26 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and its facilities became the company's Southwark brewery, which still operates.\n\n==History==\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord = {{coord|-34.8958| 138.6175}} <!--latitude and longitude as a +/- decimal.-->\n| zoom = 16 <!--(1=whole world, 18=a street)-->\n| width = 300\n| height = 350\n| shape1=n-square\n| shape-color1=blue\n| shape-outline1=white\n| mark-coord1 = {{coord|-34.894 | 138.6182}}\n| mark-title1 = Walkerville Brewery Lots 66, 67\n| mark-coord2 = {{coord|-34.8958 | 138.6171}}\n| mark-title2 = Lot 41 Walkerville\n| caption = Walkerville Tce is highlighted yellow. The section beyond Fuller Street is not seen on early maps.\n| auto-caption=1\n}}\n\nThe first brewery in Walkerville was founded by William Colyer and William Williams, South Australia's first licensed publican.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article159532901 |title=Licensed Victuallers' Society |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=VIII |issue=351 |location=South Australia |date=16 March 1850 |accessdate=25 February 2018 |page=2 (Supplement to the \"Adelaide Observer\") |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The partnership was dissolved late the same year, Colyer returned to England.,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158919398 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |issue=74 |location=South Australia |date=23 November 1844 |accessdate=24 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nWilliams embarked on a program of expansion. He commissioned architect Thomas Price<ref>Price was active in Adelaide 1845\u201350; laid out the suburb Knightsbridge (became part of [[Leabrook, South Australia|Leabrook]]), designed New Queen's Theatre for [[George Coppin]], a housing estate for [[Bean Brothers|George Bean]], grandstand at the [[Old Adelaide Racecourse]] and did much dealing in real estate.</ref> to erect new buildings on Fuller Street in 1846,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71606683 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The South Australian]] |volume=IX |issue=792 |location=South Australia |date=11 December 1846 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> identified as Lots 66 and 67,<ref name=Lewis/> although Lots 64 and 65 on the other side of Walkerville Terrace (also known as Richmond Road) closer to the Torrens would seem more likely.\nA series of tunnels running down to the [[River Torrens|Torrens]] from Fuller Street and Warwick Street served as cellars (filled in c. 1970 preparatory to erecting the Highways Department building).<ref name=Scales>{{cite book|title=John Walker's Village|author=Marjorie Scales|publisher=Rigby Ltd, Adelaide|year=1974|isbn=0851798292}}</ref> The \"tunnel\" story has elsewhere been debunked, and identified as nothing but drains.<ref name=Lewis/> \nWilliams was found insolvent 1851, but had his certificate annulled in 1853.\nAt some stage there was another brewery on Lot 41, Walkerville, on land purchased by N. P. Levi in October 1842,<ref name=Lewis>{{cite book|title=The Walkerville Story: 140 years|author=John Lewis|publisher=The Corporation of the Town of Walkerville|year=1988|isbn=073163067X}}</ref> but whether part of this history is as yet not determined.\n*William Williams (c. 1803 \u2013 26 April 1858),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207161191 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[Adelaide Times]] |volume=XII |issue=2297 |location=South Australia |date=28 April 1858 |accessdate=25 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> arrived 1836 aboard ''Africaine'' <ref>Not to be confused with William Williams (c. 1817 \u2013 17 August 1859), also on the \"[[First Fleet of South Australia]]\" aboard ''Cygnet'', married Maria Wickham (1820 \u2013 17 February 1872), https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/92270959 with parents aboard ''Africaine'', on 12 August 1839</ref> and was \"the first (colonist) to drink Torrens water\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38441302 |title=The Old Colonists' Festival |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XV |issue=1360 |location=South Australia |date=22 February 1851 |accessdate=1 March 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He married Jane Catchlove (c. 1811 \u2013 20 April 1885) on 2 July 1837. Jane arrived in South Australia in November 1836 aboard Tam O'Shanter with her father Edward William Catchlove and three brothers and sisters. Henry Catchlove of [[Hindmarsh Brewery]] was an uncle. William and Jane had seven children, among them William Huey Williams MD was educated at [[Adelaide Educational Institution|AEI]] and [[St Peter's College, Adelaide|SPC]], appointed  Resident House Physician, Royal infirmary Liverpool; and Mary Laura Williams (1845 \u2013 13 November 1880) married Thomas Moseley, son of [[Henry Jackson Moseley|Henry Moseley]] of Glenelg, on 25 October 1877.\n:Williams gained notoriety in 1851 for his obstruction to the formation of the Walkerville Anglican Church committee.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207066507 |title=Walkerville Church Case |newspaper=[[Adelaide Times]] |volume=II |issue=360 |location=South Australia |date=20 January 1851 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> \n:He died destitute and a subscription organised to benefit his widow and seven children<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49772847 |title=Provision for the Widow |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XXII |issue=3629 |location=South Australia |date=25 May 1858 |accessdate=1 March 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> was well patronised.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158125140 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=XVI |issue=869 |location=South Australia |date=29 May 1858 |accessdate=1 March 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n<!--only two found in GDB: Mary Laura 1845 and Frederich 1847; no mention of Mary Williams (c. 1848 \u2013 14 October 1919) who married George Moseley (1850\u2013 ) on 25 November 1875.-->\nEdmund Levi, brother of Philip, the property's owner, took over management of Walkerville Brewery in 1853,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39813610 |title=Insolvency Court |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XXXIX |issue=8607 |location=South Australia |date=17 June 1874 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> leasing it to one James Thomson.\nIn January 1860 fire destroyed the malthouse, which had been leased to Richard Goss<!--father of William, Frances, Francis--> (died 1869), who sold malt to Simms as well as to Thomson. In 1854 Thomson relinquished his share of the business<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48552610 |title=Notice to Innkeepers: Walkerville Brewery |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XVIII |issue=2354 |location=South Australia |date=2 April 1854 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and in October left the partnership to White & Phillips<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49201658 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XIII |issue=2529 |location=South Australia |date=30 October 1854 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> who shortly went bankrupt.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49765148 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XXI |issue=3289 |location=South Australia |date=21 April 1857 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}} Samuel Vincent Price Phillips,</ref> Thomson was found insolvent in 1864 and jailed for two months.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article159527679 |title=Law and Criminal Courts - Insolvency Court. |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=XXII |issue=1209 |location=South Australia |date=3 December 1864 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He was not clearly related to [[James Turnbull Thomson]], brewer and founder of [[Balhannah, South Australia|Balhannnah]], who had more than his share of financial failures.\n*William Hardyman Colyer (17 January 1816 \u2013 15 August 1891 in [[Rondebosch]]) arrived in South Australia aboard ''Winchester'' September 1838, and acted as brewer for a company in Launceston<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66022313 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Cornwall Chronicle]] |volume=9 |issue=468 |location=Tasmania, Australia |date=11 November 1843 |accessdate=24 February 2018 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> before in 1844 founding a brewery in [[Walkerville, South Australia]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27446662 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=South Australia |date=28 February 1844 |accessdate=25 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}It is likely he acted as consultant, setting up a brewery, training a successor and moving on.</ref> He later settled in [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southafricansettlers.com/?p=21462|title=South African Settlers: William Hardyman Colyer|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref> \n*Edmund Levi (1827 \u2013 30 July 1895) arrived in Adelaide in 1842, joined brother Philip's P. Levi & Co. in 1854. He married Gertrude Goldsmid in 1862.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article34518082 |title=Death of Mr. Edmund Levi |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XXXVIII |issue=11478 |location=South Australia |date=1 August 1895 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Charles White ( \u2013 ) <!--perhaps (c. 1834 \u2013 5 June 1917)--> was chairman of the first Council of the District of Walkerville, with councillors J. H. Swann, John Campbell, J. D. Woods, and Thomas Beadle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article129738886 |title=Municipal Fathers |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)]] |volume=VII |issue=958 |location=South Australia |date=9 August 1926 |accessdate=24 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}List of Walkerville Council chairmen</ref>\n*Samuel Vincent Price <!--Price in SA, Pryce everywhere else--> Phillips ( \u2013 c. 1896) left for the goldfields c. 1858, died in England.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article190611549 |title=Probate and Administration |newspaper=[[The Age]] |issue=12,899 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=3 July 1896 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*James Thomson was perhaps James Thomson \"the elder\" who arrived aboard ''Moffat'' December 1839 with wife Mary (c. 1791 \u2013 5 April 1875), with children Emma and Thomas, founded Sussex Arms Hotel 1843, died before 1875. In 1847 his daughter Betsy Thomson (c. 1816 \u2013 12 February 1893) married James Maskall Nottage (1821 \u2013 17 December 1879),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71607508 |title=Local News. |newspaper=[[The South Australian]] |volume=X |issue=817 |location=South Australia |date=9 March 1847 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> to whom Thomson transferred the \"Sussex Arms\"' licence in 1853, and for whom Nottage Terrace was named.<ref name=district>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article64316447 |title=Walkerville, Medindie and District |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)]] |volume=LXXXVIII |issue=25,774 |location=South Australia |date=6 August 1923 |accessdate=14 February 2018 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}} Daughter Louisa Thomson married Benjamin Boyce ( \u2013 1 December 1847), subject of [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/boyce-benjamin-12813 ADB article], on 26 September 1843</ref>\n\nAround 1862 Ball & Huntley took over Thomson's defunct brewery, named it the \"Black Horse Brewery\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Hallett Shuehard and David Tuckwell|title=Brewers and aerated Water Manufacturers in South Australia 1836\u20131936|isbn=0-646-14678-5|year=1992}}</ref><ref name=Walkerville>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article26756621 |title=The Walkerville Brewery |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XXXIII |issue=9899 |location=South Australia |date=10 July 1890 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and began brewing there again, purchasing the property in 1870.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article39175006 |title=The Breweries of Adelaide and Its Suburbs |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=XXXII |issue=6729 |location=South Australia |date=1 June 1868 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nTheir malthouse was destroyed by fire on 5 June 1871. Ball died in 1882 and Huntley continued operating the brewery until 1890<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5547777 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=LX |issue=18,369 |location=South Australia |date=28 August 1917 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> when he retired.\n\n*George Ball (c. 1831 \u2013 1 November 1882) and his wife Anna Jane Ball (c. 1834 \u2013 4 June 1924) arrived in Adelaide aboard emigrant ship ''China'' in November 1852.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57389926 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)]] |volume=LXXXIX |issue=26,035 |location=South Australia |date=6 June 1924 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*George Huntley (5 February 1832 \u2013 9 August 1917) arrived in Adelaide around 1851,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5547777 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=LX |issue=18,369 |location=South Australia |date=28 August 1917 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> worked as a builder, then for White & Phillips, brewers. In September 1855 he married Mary Ann Clarke, widow of Joseph Clarke of Walkerville.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article164135062 |title=Mr. George Huntley. |newspaper=[[The Observer (Adelaide)]] |volume=LXXIV |issue=5,661 |location=South Australia |date=1 September 1917 |accessdate=14 February 2018 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}} Joseph and Mary Ann Clarke arrived aboard Harpley, perhaps refugees from France, in September 1848. Joseph's death was not reported in newspapers or in BMD lists, perhaps interstate.</ref>\n\nIn 1889 the brewery was taken over and run as a co-operative by a consortium of four \"free\" hotel owners: Robert Hyman, John Selby Cocker, Samuel Harris, and Vincent Henry Simpson.<ref name=Walkerville/>\n*Robert Hyman (1851 \u2013 December 1903), a Finnish-born hotelkeeper, was a founder of Walkerville Brewery Co-operative in 1889 and remained one of the largest shareholders m that business and on board of directors from 1886 to 1903.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article163039401 |title=Oituary |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |volume=LX |issue=3,247 |location=South Australia |date=26 December 1903 |accessdate=8 February 2018 |page=31 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He married Sarah North in 1876; a granddaughter Gwendoline Kathleen Hyman (1903\u20131992) on 16 February 1926) married [[Alfred von Doussa|Louis Alfred von Doussa]] in 1926\n*John Selby Cocker (c. 1844 \u2013 14 April 1901) arrived with his father aboard ''Hooghly'' in October 1846, worked on the [[Australian Overland Telegraph Line|Overland Telegraph Line]], then as a baker before taking over his father's Kentish Arms Hotel on Stanley Street, North Adelaide. He was one of the four original members of the Co-operative. He married Joan Agnes Dineen in 1878.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4833385 |title=The Late Mr. J. S. Cocker |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XLIII |issue=13,262 |location=South Australia |date=20 April 1901 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Samuel Harris (c. 1844 \u2013 23 February 1904) arrived in South Australia with his parents aboard ''John Bunyan'' in 1854. After many years with the coachmaking firm of Barlow & Sons he became landlord, then publican of the Gasworks Hotel in Brompton. He was chairman of directors of the Walkerville Co-operative for ten years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4947254 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XLVI |issue=14,150 |location=South Australia |date=24 February 1904 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Vincent Henry Simpson (1860 \u2013 12 July 1926) was born in Norwood a son of Frederick John Simpson (died 1883), and educated at Unwin's school in North Adelaide. He was publican of the Buckingham Arms, Gilberton at an early age, and married Emily Chittleborough (  \u20131952) in 1885. He was chairman of directors of the Co-operative.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46529483 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=14 July 1926 |accessdate=11 February 2018 |page=16 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe Walkerville Brewing Company was founded with 19 other shareholders, all publicans or hotel owners, whose share of the profits depended on the amount of trade they did with the company.\n\nThe company merged with Clark and Ware's company and its operations moved to Southwark, but the Walkerville Brewery had one last spasm when it was resurrected by Charles Williams in 1901 and operated for five more years before closing for the last time; see below for more information.\n\n==Amalgamations==\n;Torrenside Brewery\nFrequently spelled \"Torrensside\", the brewery was founded by the [[Port Road, Adelaide|Port Road]] Southwark, now [[Thebarton, South Australia|Thebarton]], on the banks of the Torrens in 1886 by A. W. & T. L. Ware. Their first customer was the Exchange Hotel, operated by their brothers George and Boxer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36328197 |title=The Torrenside Brewery |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |volume=XXVIII |issue=8600 |location=South Australia |date=12 May 1886 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe Ware brothers were sons of Charles James Ware (c. 1824 \u2013 19 December 1891) who arrived in SA aboard ''Augustus'' in November 1846 and married Fanny Crawford (1829 \u2013 7 April 1898) on 22 August 1859. Fanny arrived with her parents aboard ''D'Auvergne'' in March 1839. Fanny was the daughter of William Crawford, Builder. Charles ran the Burra Hotel, then in 1868 took over the Exchange Hotel, owned by Sir [[Henry Ayers]]. \n*Arthur Wellington Ware CMG (1861 \u2013 29 January 1927) Mayor of Adelaide 1898\u20131901. He married Rosa Henrietta Haussen (2 November 1860 \u2013 29 November 1915) of the [[Hindmarsh Brewery]] Haussen family, on 11 March 1884.\n*Thomas Lincoln \"Tom\" Ware (1864 \u2013 22 December 1896) died while swimming near the [[Grange, South Australia|Grange]] jetty.\n*George James Ware (15 February 1867 \u2013 17 June 1948) \n*(Charles) Boxer Ware (26 December 1870 \u2013 23 July 1932) was educated at [[Stanley Grammar School]], [[Watervale, South Australia|Watervale]], served as mayor of [[City of West Torrens|Thebarton]] for four years and for some time chairman of directors, Walkerville Co-operative Brewing.\n\n;East Adelaide Brewery\nEdward Clark, son of [[W. H. Clark (brewer)|W. H. Clark]], was brewer for the Murray Brewery in [[Goolwa, South Australia|Goolwa]] in the 1880s, formed E. Clark & Co. in Adelaide with one A. Wheelwright, was found insolvent in 1889 through lack of capital, then served as brewer for the Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company. He left the Co-operative in 1895 to manage the East Adelaide Brewery, a two-storey establishment which the newly revived E. Clark & Co. built on the south side of the River Torrens, on Walkerville Road (now Stephen Terrace).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article166458866 |title=The East Adelaide Brewery |newspaper=[[Quiz And The Lantern]] |volume=IX |issue=422 |location=South Australia |date=23 September 1897 |accessdate=27 February 2018 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The probable location is about 1{{nbsp}}km south of the Walkerville Brewery.\n\nE. Clark & Co. was founded with twelve shareholders inc. William Warren, James Wells, and Eliza Dreyer<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article165619439 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Observer (Adelaide)]] |volume=LXXXIII |issue=7,037 |location=South Australia |date=2 October 1926 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=20 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> as Clark & Co., became Clark, Ware & Co. before absorbing the old Walkerville Brewing Company.\n* William Walter Warren (c. 1860 \u2013 24 February 1938) may have had a hotel, but was better known as a racehorse breeder.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131906564 |title=Mr. W. Warren Dead: Saw 54 Melbourne Cups |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)]] |volume=XXX |issue=4,553 |location=South Australia |date=25 February 1938 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*James Samuel Wells (1872\u20131959), son of Michael Wells ( \u2013 14 August 1887) and Elizabeth Wells n\u00e9e Davis ( \u2013 ), owners of Parkside Hotel.\n*Eliza Jane Dreyer (c. 1861 \u2013 25 September 1926) had Prince Albert Hotel in Wright street for 30 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54872728 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)]] |volume=XCI |issue=26,555 |location=South Australia |date=27 September 1926 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=11 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nThe product proved so popular the factory's capacity had to be doubled a year later. In 1897 a bottling plant was installed and production capacity doubled again. By 1898 the East Adelaide Brewery was contracted to supply fifty \"free houses\", and once again a doubling of capacity was deemed necessary to keep up with demand.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54543933 |title=Amalgamation of Two Breweries |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=LXIII |issue=16,039 |location=South Australia |date=9 April 1898 |accessdate=12 February 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nIt was decided instead to amalgamate with the Wares' Torrenside Brewery, which took place in April 1898, their owners combining as Clark, Ware & Co.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article209134789 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Express and Telegraph]] |volume=XXXV |issue=10,336 |location=South Australia |date=9 April 1898 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}.</ref>\nThe East Adelaide premises were closed and the Torrenside brewery at Southwark expanded.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article29402231 |title=Enterprising Brewers |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=9 April 1898 |accessdate=10 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;Walkerville Co-operative\nIn 1899 the activities of the Walkerville Brewing Company and Clark, Ware & Co. combined as Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company at Southwark. Additional buildings were erected at the site.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54852723 |title=Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |volume=LXIV |issue=16,548 |location=South Australia |date=25 November 1899 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nThe old Walkerville Brewery was taken over by its erstwhile head brewer Charles Williams in 1901<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4848269 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |volume=XLIV |issue=13,340 |location=South Australia |date=20 July 1901 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and operated successfully as \"Williams' Walkerville Brewery\", with outlets at the Tea Tree Gully Hotel<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article166341746 |title=Advertising |newspaper=[[Quiz (Adelaide newspaper)]] |volume=XVII |issue=870 |location=South Australia |date=1 June 1906 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=9 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and perhaps a few others not tied to either of the two combines, no doubt to the chagrin of the Co-operative, which bought out the company in 1906.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5085148 |title=A Brewery Combine |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |volume=XLVIII |issue=14,881 |location=South Australia |date=28 June 1906 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*[[Samuel Joshua Jacobs]] (1853 \u2013 1937) was chairman of directors from the formation of the Company, succeeded by C. Boxer Ware. He was also president of Chamber of Commerce, and of United Chambers of Manufacture, chairman of [[Adelaide Tattersalls Club|Tattersalls Racing Club]].\n*Charles Williams (c. 1850 \u2013 c. 12 April 1936) was born in Adelaide, educated at [[J. L. Young]]'s [[Adelaide Educational Institution]], worked at the brewery his father John Williams (c. 1806 \u2013 29 June 1876) owned at [[Angas Park, South Australia|Angas Park]], then in [[Ballarat]]. He became head brewer at the [[Lion Brewing and Malting Company]] and for the Walkerville Brewing Company. When that company moved to Southwark he reopened the old facility and continued brewing for another five years. After ten years' inactivity he became brewer for the [[Waverley Brewery]], Mitcham and retired at the age of 83.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74156283 |title=Obituary |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=18 April 1936 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=21 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Relationship, if any, to William Williams, Adelaide's first publican and founder of Walkerville Brewery has not been determined.\nA popular drink produced by the Walkerville Co-op was K\u00f6nig Lager, whose name was changed to Adelaide Lager in 1914 amid the anti-German sentiment that swept Australia and resulted in wholesale [[List of Australian place names changed from German names|changing of German-sounding place names]].\nThe Walkerville Co-Operative Brewing Co. continued its growth and by the end of World War I was the largest brewery in South Australia.\n\nIn September 1925 Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company, Limited, was first listed on the Adelaide Stock Exchange. Directors were Charles Boxer Ware, Frederick James Blades, Vincent Henry Simpson, and William Walter Warren.\n\nThe company absorbed [[Hindmarsh Brewery|Haussen's Brewery]] in 1926; Haussen & Co. retained ownership of its string of hotels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54823647 |title=Walkerville Brewery Development |newspaper=[[The Register (Adelaide)]] |volume=XCI |issue=26,598 |location=South Australia |date=16 November 1926 |accessdate=9 February 2018 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1925 the Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company Ltd signed an agreement with the Nathan Institute of Z\u01d4rich for the installation of a \"Nathan patent\" plant at the company's brewery at Southwark, and has been claimed as the first Australian adopter of the system. It was a major project for the brewery, requiring the erection of additional buildings to accommodate the new equipment. Beer production commenced in the Nathan plant late in 1927, and a formal opening ceremony was held in January 1928. However Nathan's process was in operation at [[Peter Grant Hay]]'s Richmond N.S. Brewery in 1927, so although they signed the contract earlier, Southwark brewery was the second in Australia to implement the system.\n*[[Leopold Nathan]], born 30 July 1864 in [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg|W\u00fcrttemberg]], Germany, invented a closed brewing system in [[cylindro-conical]] vessels, which he began marketing in the 1920s. His system removed many of the uncertainties in the brewing process, ensuring a reliable, consistent, high quality product.\n\nThe company made substantial losses in the year 1928\u201329.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article215997590 |title=The Liquor Trades and Licensed Victuallers' World |newspaper=[[The Sport (Adelaide newspaper)]] |volume=XIX |issue=998 |location=South Australia |date=7 November 1929 |accessdate=9 February 2018 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n;South Australian Brewing Company\nThe Walkerville Co-operative Brewing Company Ltd. was bought out by the [[South Australian Brewing Company]] in 1939 and its facilities became the company's main brewery, which still operates at the same location, and in 1949 was renamed from Walkerville brewery to Southwark Brewery.\n\nWalkerville Nathan beer was renamed Southwark beer in November 1951.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130913474 |title=Nathan Beer Renamed: \"Same Brew\" |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)]] |volume=57 |issue=8,818 |location=South Australia |date=12 November 1951 |accessdate=28 February 2018 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beeradelaide.com/blog.php?ID=10048|title=Beer Adelaide: Southwark Bitter|access-date=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\nAn article on the practicalities of beer brewing in Adelaide ([[West End Brewery|West End]], [[Kent Town Brewery|Kent Town]], [[Union Brewery (Adelaide)|Union]], [[Pirie Street Brewery|Pirie Street]], [[Hindmarsh Brewery|Hindmarsh]], [[Morphett Street Brewery|Morphett Street]], and Walkerville breweries) in the late 1860s may be read [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/39175006 here].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1844 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:1927 disestablishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Beer brewing companies based in South Australia]]\n[[Category:Breweries in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "ScottDavis", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikilink Africaine", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walkerville_Brewery"}
{"title_page": "Kingdom of Benin", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|native_name         = ''Edo''\n|conventional_long_name = Kingdom of Benin\n|common_name         = Benin Kingdom\n|country             = \n|era                 = \n|status              = \n|status_text         = \n|government_type     = [[Monarchy]]\n|year_start          = 1180\n|year_end            = 1897\n|event_start         = \n|date_start          = \n|event_end           = Annexed by the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n|date_end            = \n|p1                  = Igodomigodo\n|flag_p1             = Transparent_flag_with_question_mark.png\n|s1                  = Southern Nigeria Protectorate\n|flag_s1             = Flag of the Southern Nigeria Protectorate (1900\u20131914).svg\n|image_map           = Benin 1625 locator.png\n|image_map_caption   = The extent of Benin in 1625\n|capital             = Edo<br/>(now [[Benin City]])\n|common_languages    = [[Edo language|Edo]]\n|religion            = \n|currency            = \n|leader1             = Eweka I <ref>Ben-Amos, Paula Girshick (1995). The Art of Benin Revised Edition. British Museum Press. p. 20. {{ISBN|0-7141-2520-2}}.</ref>\n|leader2             = [[Ewuare]] (1440\u20131473)\n|leader3             = [[Ovonramwen]] (exile 1897)\n|leader4             = [[Erediauwa I]] (post-imperial)\n|leader5             = [[Ewuare II]] (post-imperial)\n|year_leader1        = 1180\u20131246\n|year_leader2        = 1440\u20131473\n|year_leader4        = 1978\u20132016\n|year_leader5        = 2016-\n|title_leader        = [[Oba of Benin#List of Obas of the Benin Empire (1180-present)|King/Emperor (Oba)]]\n|<!-- Area and population of a given year -->\n|stat_year1          = 1625\n|stat_area1          = 90000\n|stat_pop1           = \n|today               = {{flag|Nigeria}}\n|demonym=|area_km2=|area_rank=|GDP_PPP=|GDP_PPP_year=|HDI=|HDI_year=}}\n\nThe '''Kingdom of Benin''', also known as the '''Benin Kingdom''', was a pre-[[Colonisation of Africa|colonial]] kingdom in what is now southern [[Nigeria]]. It is not to be confused with [[Benin]], the post-colonial nation state. The Kingdom of Benin's capital was Edo, now known as [[Benin City]] in [[Edo State|Edo state]]. The Benin Kingdom was \"one of the oldest and most highly developed states in the coastal hinterland of [[West Africa]], dating perhaps to the eleventh century CE\",{{sfn|Strayer|2013|pp=695-696}} until it was annexed by the [[British Empire]] in 1897.\n\n==Oral traditions==\n\nThe original people and founders of the Benin Kingdom, the [[Edo people]], were initially ruled by the [[List of the Ogiso|Ogiso]] (Kings of the Sky) who called their land [[Igodomigodo]]. The first Ogiso (Ogiso Igodo), wielded much influence and gained popularity as a good ruler. He died after a long reign and was succeeded by Ere, his eldest son. In the 12th century, a great [[palace]] intrigue erupted and crown prince Ekaladerhan, the only son of the last Ogiso, was sentenced to death as a result of the first queen (who was barren) deliberately changing an oracle's message to the Ogiso. In carrying out the royal order that he be killed, the palace messengers had mercy and set the prince free at [[Ughoton]] near Benin. When his father the Ogiso died, the Ogiso dynasty officially ended. The people and royal kingmakers preferred their late king's son as the next to rule.\n\nThe exiled Prince Ekaladerhan had by this time changed his name to Izoduwa (meaning 'I have chosen the path of prosperity') and found his way to [[Ile-Ife]]. It was during this period of confusion in Benin that the elders, led by Chief Oliha, mounted a search for the banished Prince Ekaladerhan - whom the Ife people now called [[Oduduwa]]. Oduduwa, who could not return due to his advanced age, granted them Oranmiyan, his grandson, to rule over them. Oranmiyan was resisted by Ogiamien Irebor, one of the palace chiefs, and took up his abode in the palace built for him at Usama by the elders (now a [[coronation]] [[shrine]]). Soon after his arrival, he married a beautiful lady, Erinmwinde, daughter of Ogie-Egor, the ninth Enogie of Egor, by whom he had a son. After residing there for some years he called a meeting of the people and renounced his office, remarking in vexation ''Ile-Ibinu'' (\"ile\" means land, \"binu\" mean anger, and thus the kingdom was called Ibinu, which was mispronounced Bini in the 15th and 16th centuries by the Portuguese). This was out of frustration as he often expressed that \"only a child born, trained and educated in the arts and mysteries of the land could reign over the people\". He arranged for his son born to him by Erinmwinde, Eweka, to be made king in his place, and returned to Yorubaland thereafter. His son the new king was soon found to be deaf and dumb, and so the elders appealed to Oranmiyan. He gave them charmed seeds known as \"omo ayo\" to play with, saying that to do so will make him talk. The little Eweka played with the seeds with his peers at Egor, his mother's hometown. While playing with the seeds, he announced \"Owomika\" as his royal name. Thus, he gave rise to the tradition of the subsequent Obas of Benin spending seven days and nights at Usama before proceeding to announce their royal names at Egor. Eweka thus started a dynasty that now bears his name. Oranmiyan went on to serve as the founder of the [[Oyo Empire]], where he ruled as the first [[Alaafin]] of Oyo. His descendants now rule in Ile Ife, Oyo and Benin.\n\nBy the 15th century, Benin had expanded into a thriving city-state. The twelfth Oba in the line, Oba [[Ewuare|Ewuare the Great]] (1440\u20131473) would expand the [[city-state]]'s territories to surrounding regions.\n\nIt was not until the 15th century, during the reign of Oba Ewuare the Great, that the kingdom's administrative centre, the city of Ubinu (or Ibinu), began to be known as [[Benin City]] by the [[Portugal|Portuguese]], a pronunciation later adopted by the locals as well. The Portuguese would write this down as Benin City. Edo's neighbours, such as the Itsekiris and the Urhobos, continued to refer to the city as Ubini up until the late 19th century.\n\nAside from Benin City, the system of rule of the Oba in the empire, even through the golden age of the kingdom, was still loosely based upon the Ogiso dynasty's tradition, which was military protection in exchange for pledged allegiance and taxes paid to the royal administrative centre. The language and culture was not enforced, as the empire remained heterogeneous and localized according to each group within the kingdom, though a local enogie (or duke) was often appointed by the Oba for specific ethnic areas.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Early history ===\nBy the 1st century BCE, the Benin territory was partially agricultural; and it became primarily agricultural by around 500 CE, but hunting and gathering still remained important. Also by 500 CE, [[iron]] was in use by the inhabitants of the Benin territory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bondarenko|first=Dmitri|last2=Roese|first2=Peter|date=1999-01-01|title=Benin Prehistory. The Origin and Settling Down of the Edo|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/283567896_Benin_Prehistory_The_Origin_and_Settling_Down_of_the_Edo|journal=Anthropos: International Review of Anthropology and Linguistics|volume=94|pages=542\u2013552}}</ref>\n\nBenin City (formerly Edo) sprang up by around 1000 CE, in a forest that could be easily defended. The dense vegetation and narrow paths made the city easy to defend against attacks. The [[rainforest]], which Benin City is situated in, helped in the development of the city because of its vast resources \u2014 fish from rivers and creeks, animals to hunt, leaves for roofing, plants for medicine, ivory for carving and trading, and wood for boat building \u2014 that could be exploited. However, domesticated animals, from the forest and surrounding areas, could not survive, due to a disease spread by [[Tsetse fly|tsetse flies]]; after centuries of exposure, some animals, such as cattle and goat, developed a resistance to the disease.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Forgotten Africa: An Introduction to Its Archaeology|last=Connah|first=Graham|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|isbn=978-0415305914|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/forgottenafricai00grah/page/125 125-6]|url=https://archive.org/details/forgottenafricai00grah/page/125}}</ref>\n\nThe original name of the Benin Kingdom, at its creation some time in the first millennium [[Common Era|CE]], was [[Igodomigodo]], as its inhabitants called it. Their ruler was called [[Ogiso]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Cahoon |url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Nigeria_native.html |title=Nigerian Traditional States |website=Worldstatesmen.org |date= |accessdate=2016-11-17}}</ref> Nearly 36 known Ogiso are accounted for as rulers of this initial incarnation of the state.\n\n{{short description|Series of earthworks around present-day Benin City, Nigeria}}\n[[File:Ancient_Benin_city.JPG|thumb|Depiction of [[Benin City]] of 1668. In the center there is a wall like structure, which probably are the walls of Benin.]]\nThe '''Walls of Benin''' are a series of [[Earthworks (archaeology)|earthworks]] made up of banks and ditches, called ''{{font|I|font=serif}}ya'' in the [[Edo language]] in the area around present-day [[Benin City]], the capital of present-day [[Edo State|Edo]], [[Nigeria]]. They consist of {{convert|15|km|abbr=off}} of city iya  and an estimated {{convert|16000|km|abbr=off}}  in the rural area around Benin.<ref name=\"Protection\">{{cite book |author1=Patrick Darling |editor1-last=Korka |editor1-first=Elena |title=The Protection of Archaeological Heritage in Times of Economic Crisis |date=2015 |publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing |isbn=9781443874113 |page=341\u2013352 |chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B_imBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA353&dq=Walls+of+Benin+%22Patrick+Darling%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiis5CU_fTgAhUsShUIHRhaC7UQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=Walls%20of%20Benin%20&f=false |accessdate=9 March 2019 |language=en |chapter=Conservation Management of the Benin Earthworks of Southern Nigeria: A critical review of past and present action plans}}</ref> Some estimates suggest that the walls of Benin may have been constructed between the thirteenth and mid-fifteenth century CE<ref name=\"Ogundiran\">{{cite journal |last1=Ogundiran |first1=Akinwumi |title=Four Millennia of Cultural History in Nigeria (ca. 2000 B.C.\u2013A.D. 1900): Archaeological Perspectives |journal=Journal of World Prehistory |date=June 2005 |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=133\u2013168|doi=10.1007/s10963-006-9003-y }}</ref> and others suggest that the walls of Benin (in the Esan region) may have been constructed during the first millennium CE.<ref name=\"Ogundiran\"/><ref name=\"MacEachern\">{{cite journal |last1=MacEachern |first1=Scott |title=Two thousand years of West African history |url=https://www.academia.edu/831918 |journal=African Archaeology: A Critical Introduction |publisher=Academia}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== First Encounters and Records ===\nThe Benin City walls have been known to Westerners since around 1500. Around 1500, the Portuguese explorer [[Duarte Pacheco Pereira]], briefly described the walls during his travels. Another description given around 1600, one hundred years after Pereira's description, is by the Dutch explorer Dierick Ruiters.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|date=June 1967|journal=Journal of the Historical Society of Nigeria|volume=3|issue=4|pages=597\u2013599|issn=0018-2540|jstor=41856902|title=New Light on the Benin City Walls}}</ref>\n\nPereira's account of the walls is as follows: \n\n{{quote|This city is about a [[League (unit)|league]] long from gate to gate; it has no wall but is surrounded by a large moat, very wide and deep, which suffices for its defence.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nigerian Perspectives: An Historical Anthology|last=Hodgkin|first=Thomas|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1960|isbn=978-0192154347|location=|pages=93}}</ref>}}\nThe [[Archaeology|archaeologist]] [[Graham Connah]] suggests that Pereira was mistaken with his description by saying that there was no wall. Connah says, \"[Pereira] considered that a bank of earth was not a wall in the sense of the Europe of his day.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRuiters' account of the walls is as follows:\n\n{{quote|At the gate where I entered on horseback, I saw a very high bulwark, very thick of earth, with a very deep broad ditch, but it was dry, and full of high trees... That gate is a reasonable good gate, made of wood in their manner, which is to be shut, and there always there is watch holden.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nigerian Perspectives: An Historical Anthology|last=Hodgkin|first=Thomas|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1960|isbn=978-0192154347|location=|pages=120}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Construction ===\nEstimates for the initial construction of the walls range from the first millennium CE to the mid-fifteenth century CE. According to Connah, oral tradition and travelers' accounts suggest a construction date of 1450-1500 CE.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|date=January 1972|title=Archaeology of Benin|journal=The Journal of African History|volume=13|issue=1|pages=33|doi=10.1017/S0021853700000244}}</ref> It has been estimated that, assuming a 10 hour work day, a labour force of 5,000 men could have completed the walls within 97 days, or by 2,421 men in 200 days. However, these estimates have been criticized for not taking into account the time it would have taken to extract earth from an ever deepening hole and the time it would have taken to heap the earth into a high bank.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|date=June 1967|journal=Journal of the Historical Society of Nigeria|volume=3|issue=4|pages=608|issn=0018-2540|jstor=41856902|title=New Light on the Benin City Walls}}</ref> It is unknown whether slavery or some other type of labour was used in the construction of the walls.\n\n==Description==\n\nThe walls were built of a ditch and dike structure; the ditch dug to form an inner moat with the excavated earth used to form the exterior rampart.\n\nThe Benin Walls were ravaged by the British in 1897 during what has come to be called the ''[[Benin Expedition of 1897|Punitive expedition]]''. Scattered pieces of the structure remain in Edo, with the vast majority of them being used by the locals for building purposes. What remains of the wall itself continues to be torn down for real estate developments.<ref>http://www.beninmoatfoundation.org/clarioncall.html  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725061950/http://www.beninmoatfoundation.org/clarioncall.html |date=July 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n[[Fred Pearce]] wrote in New Scientist:\n<div>{{quote|They extend for some 16,000&nbsp;km in all, in a mosaic of more than 500 interconnected settlement boundaries. They cover 2,510 sq. miles (6,500 square kilometres) and were all dug by the [[Edo State|Edo]] people. In all, they are four times longer than the [[Great Wall of China]], and consumed a hundred times more material than the [[Great Pyramid of Cheops]]. They took an estimated 150 million hours of digging to construct, and are perhaps the largest single archaeological phenomenon on the planet.<ref name=\"African Queen\">Pearce, Fred. [https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg16322035.100-the-african-queen.html?page=2 ''African Queen'']. New Scientist, 11 September 1999, Issue 2203.</ref>}}</div>\n<div>\n[[Ethnomathematics|Ethnomathematician]]  [[Ron Eglash]] has discussed the planned layout of the city using [[fractals]] as the basis, not only in the city itself and the villages but even in the rooms of houses. He commented that \"When Europeans first came to Africa, they considered the architecture very disorganised and thus primitive. It never occurred to them that the Africans might have been using a form of mathematics that they hadn\u2019t even discovered yet.\"<ref name=\"Koutonin\">{{cite news|last1=Koutonin|first1=Mawuna|title=Story of cities #5: Benin City, the mighty medieval capital now lost without trace|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2016/mar/18/story-of-cities-5-benin-city-edo-nigeria-mighty-medieval-capital-lost-without-trace|accessdate=2 April 2018|date=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"250px\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Ancient Benin city.JPG|[[Benin city]] in the 17th century.\nFile:Drawing of Benin City made by an English officer 1897.jpg|Benin in 1897\n</gallery>\n\n=== Later history ===\nExcavations at Benin City have revealed that it was already flourishing around 1200-1300 CE.<ref name=\":0a\">{{Cite book|title=The Cambridge History of Africa, Volume 3: From c.1050 to c.1600|last=Oliver|first=Roland|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1977|isbn=978-0521209816|location=|pages=476}}</ref>\n\nIn 1440, [[Oba Ewuare]], also known as Ewuare the Great, came to power and expanded the borders of the former city-state. It was only at this time that the administrative centre of the kingdom began to be referred to as Ubinu after the [[Yoruba language|Portuguese]]<nowiki/> word and corrupted to Bini by the [[Itsekhiri]], [[Urhobo people|Urhobo]] and Edo who all lived together in the royal administrative centre of the kingdom. The Portuguese who arrived in an expedition led by Joao Afonso de Aveiro in 1485 would refer to it as Benin and the centre would become known as Benin City.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe Kingdom of Benin eventually gained political strength and ascendancy over much of what is now mid-western Nigeria.\n\nBy the seventeenth century CE, the Kingdom began to decline. Multiple civil wars broke out and disputes over the kingship took place.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Kingdom of Benin in West Africa|last=Millar|first=Heather|publisher=Benchmark Books|year=1996|isbn=978-0761400882|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kingdomofbeninin00mill/page/14 14]|url=https://archive.org/details/kingdomofbeninin00mill/page/14}}</ref>\n\n==Rituals and Law==\n\n=== Human Sacrifice ===\nForty-one female skeletons thrown into a pit were discovered by the [[archaeologist]] [[Graham Connah]]. These findings indicate that [[human sacrifice]] took place in Benin City since the thirteenth century CE.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Understanding Early Civilizations: A Comparative Study|last=Trigger|first=Bruce G.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-521-822459|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/479 479]|oclc=50291226|url=https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/479}}</ref> From the early days, human sacrifices were a part of the state religion. But many of the sensationalist accounts of the sacrifices, says [[historian]] J.D. Graham, are largely exaggerated or based on rumour and speculation. He says that all of the evidence \"points to a limited, ritual custom of human sacrifice.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Graham|first=James D.|date=1965|title=The Slave Trade, Depopulation and Human Sacrifice in Benin History: The General Approach|journal=Cahiers d'\u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=5|issue=18|pages=327\u201330|jstor=4390897}}</ref>\n\nHumans were sacrificed in an annual ritual in honour of the god of iron, where warriors from Benin City would perform an acrobatic dance while suspended from the trees. The ritual recalled a mythical war against the sky.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=The Benin Kingdom and the Edo-speaking Peoples of South-western Nigeria|last=Bradbury|first=R.E.|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=978-1315293837|location=|pages=54\u20138}}</ref>\n\nSacrifices of a man, a woman, a goat, a cow and a ram were also made to a god quite literally called \"the king of death.\" The god, named Ogiuwu, was worshipped at a special altar in the centre of Benin City.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThere were two separate annual series of rites that honoured past Obas. Sacrifices were performed every fifth day. At the end of each series of rites, the current Oba's own father was honoured with a public festival. During the festival, twelve criminals, chosen from a prison where the worst criminals were held, were sacrificed.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nBy the end of the eighteenth century, three to four people were sacrificed at the mouth of the Benin River annually, to attract European trade.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Law|first=Robin|date=January 1985|title=Human Sacrifice in Pre-Colonial West Africa|journal=African Affairs|volume=84|issue=334|pages=65|jstor=722523}}</ref>\n\nAt the burial rituals of Obas, human sacrifice was present; bodyguards of the Oba include those sacrificed. Additionally, wives and slaves of the Oba committed suicide, so that they could continue serving him in the afterlife.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Understanding Early Civilizations: A Comparative Study|last=Trigger|first=Bruce G.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-521-822459|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/88 88]|url=https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/88}}</ref>\n\n=== Burials ===\nThe monarchy of Benin was [[Hereditary monarchy|hereditary]]; the eldest son was to become the new Oba. In order to validate the succession of the kingship, the eldest son had to bury his father and perform elaborate rituals. If the eldest son failed to complete these tasks, the eldest son might be disqualified from becoming king.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Understanding Early Civilizations: A Comparative Study|last=Trigger|first=Bruce G.|date=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-82245-9|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/77 77\u201378]|oclc=50291226|url=https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/77}}</ref>\n\n=== Separation of son and mother ===\nAfter the son was installed as king, the mother was transferred to a [[palace]] just outside Benin City, in a place called Uselu. The mother held a considerable amount of power; she was, however, never allowed to meet her son \u2014 who was now divine ruler \u2014 again.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Divinity of the Oba===\nIn Benin, the Oba was seen as [[Divinity|divine]]. The Oba's divinity and sacredness was the focal point of the kingship. The Oba was shrouded in mystery; he only left his palace on ceremonial occasions. It was previously punishable by death to assert that the Oba performed human acts, such as eating, sleeping, dying, washing. The Oba was also credited with having magical powers.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Benin Kingdom and the Edo-speaking Peoples of South-western Nigeria|last=Bradbury|first=R.E.|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=978-1315293837|location=|pages=40}}</ref>\n\n==Golden Age==\nThe Oba had become the mount of power within the region. Oba Ewuare, the first ''Golden Age'' Oba, is credited with turning Benin City into a city-state from a military fortress built by the Ogisos, protected by moats and walls. It was from this bastion that he launched his military campaigns and began the expansion of the kingdom from the Edo-speaking heartlands.\n\nA series of walls marked the incremental growth of the sacred city from 850 AD until its decline in the 16th century. To enclose his palace he commanded the building of Benin's inner wall, an {{convert|7|mi|km|order=flip|adj=mid|-long|0}} earthen rampart girded by a moat {{convert|20|ft|m|order=flip|0|abbr=on}} deep. This was excavated in the early 1960s by [[Graham Connah]]. Connah estimated that its construction if spread out over five dry seasons, would have required a workforce of 1,000 laborers working ten hours a day seven days a week. Ewuare also added great thoroughfares and erected nine fortified gateways.\n\nExcavations also uncovered a rural network of earthen walls {{convert|4000|to|8000|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on|-3}} long that would have taken an estimated 150 million man-hours to build and must have taken hundreds of years to build. These were apparently raised to mark out territories for towns and cities. Thirteen years after Ewuare's death, tales of Benin's splendors lured more Portuguese traders to the city gates.<ref>Time Life Lost Civilizations series: Africa's Glorious Legacy (1994) pp.&nbsp;102\u20134</ref>\n\nAt its height, Benin dominated trade along the entire coastline from the Western Niger Delta, through Lagos to the kingdom of Great Accra (modern-day Ghana).<ref>{{cite book |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=ZPnDBAAAQBAJ |page=152 }} |title=The History of Africa: The Quest for Eternal Harmony }}</ref> It was for this reason that this coastline was named the [[Bight of Benin]]. The present-day Republic of Benin, formerly Dahomey, decided to choose the name of this bight as the name of its country. Benin ruled over the tribes of the Niger Delta including the Western Igbo, Ijaw, Itshekiri, Ika, Isoko and Urhobo amongst others. It also held sway over the Eastern Yoruba tribes of Ondo, Ekiti, Mahin/Ugbo, and Ijebu.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=B5QuAQAAIAAJ&q=orhogbua+portugal&dq=orhogbua+portugal |title=The Benin City Pilgrimage Stations |isbn=9789783153356 |last1=Aisien |first1=Ekhaguosa |year=2001 }}</ref> It also conquered what eventually became the city of [[Lagos]] hundreds of years before the British took over in 1851.<ref>{{cite book |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=MCHSd62Tse8C |page=27 }} |title=Slavery and the Birth of an African City: Lagos, 1760--1900 }}</ref>\n\nThe state developed an advanced artistic culture, especially in its famous artifacts of bronze, iron and ivory. These include bronze wall plaques and life-sized bronze heads depicting the Obas and Iyobas of Benin. The most well-known artifact is based on [[Queen Idia]], now best known as the ''[[Benin ivory mask|FESTAC Mask]]'' after its use in 1977 in the logo of the Nigeria-financed and hosted Second Festival of Black & African Arts and Culture (FESTAC 77).\n\n==European contact==\nBefore trade and contact with Europeans, supplies of metal were very scarce in Benin and writing was not present. After the Kingdom of Benin began trading with Europeans at the end of the 15th century CE, the quantity of [[bronze]] castings and thickness of casting had greatly increased; before trade with Europeans, the blades were incredibly thin and only wealthy elites could afford work with these metals that were regarded as precious.<ref name=\":0a\" /> Writing was not introduced to the Kingdom of Benin until the [[Niger Coast Protectorate|colonial period]] \u2014 near the end of the 19th century CE.<ref>Connah (2004), pp. 129</ref>\n\nThe first European travelers to reach Benin were [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] explorers under Jo\u00e3o Afonso de Aveiro in about 1485. A strong mercantile relationship developed, with the Edo trading slaves and tropical products such as [[ivory trade|ivory]], [[Black pepper|pepper]] and [[palm oil]] for European goods such as [[Manilla (money)|manillas]] and [[guns]]. In the early 16th century, the Oba sent an ambassador to [[Lisbon]], and the king of Portugal sent [[Christianity|Christian]] missionaries to Benin City. Some residents of Benin City could still speak a [[pidgin]] Portuguese in the late 19th century.\n\nThe first English expedition to Benin was in 1553, and significant trading developed between England and Benin based on the export of ivory, palm oil, pepper, and slaves. Visitors in the 16th and 19th centuries brought back to [[Europe]] tales of \"Great Benin\", a fabulous city of noble buildings, ruled over by a powerful king. This picture is for instance shown in [[Olfert Dapper]]'s [[Description of Africa (1668 book)|''Naukeurige beschrijvinge der Afrikaensche gewesten'']], published in [[Amsterdam]] in 1668.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dapper |first1=Olfert |title=Naukeurige beschrijvinge der Afrikaensche gewesten |date=1668 |publisher=[[Jacob van Meurs]] |location=Amsterdam |pages=[https://archive.org/details/gri_33125009359999/page/n676 495]-505 |url=https://archive.org/details/gri_33125009359999|quote=naukeurige beschrijvinge der afrikaensche gewesten. }}</ref> It states the following about the royal palace:\n\n''The king's court is square and located on the right-hand side of the city, as one enters it through the gate of Gotton. It is about the same size as the city of [[Haarlem]] and entirely surrounded by a special wall, comparable to the one which encircles the town. It is divided into many magnificent palaces, houses and apartments of the courtiers, and comprises beautiful and long squares with galleries, about as large as the [[Euronext Amsterdam|Exchange at Amsterdam]]. The buildings are of different sizes however, resting on wooden pillars, from top to bottom lined with copper casts, on which pictures of their war exploits and battles are engraved. All of them are being very well maintained. Most of the buildings within this court are covered with palm leaves, instead of with square planks, and every roof is adorned with a small spired tower, on which casted copper birds are standing, being very artfully sculpted and lifelike with their wings spread.''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dapper |first1=Olfert |title=Naukeurige beschrijvinge der Afrikaensche gewesten |date=1668 |publisher=Jacob van Meurs |location=Amsterdam |pages=[https://archive.org/details/gri_33125009359999/page/n676 495]-496 |url=https://archive.org/details/gri_33125009359999 |quote=495. |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAnother Dutch traveler, [[David van Nyendael]], visited Benin in 1699 and also wrote an account of the kingdom. Nyendael's description was published in 1704 as an appendix to [[Willem Bosman]]'s ''Nauwkeurige beschryving van de Guinese goud-, tand- en slave-kust''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bosman |first1=Willem |title=Nauwkeurige beschryving van de Guinese goud-, tand- en slave-kust |date=1704 |publisher=Anthony Schouten |location=Utrecht |pages=[https://archive.org/details/nauwkeurigebesch00bosm_0/page/212 212]-257 |url=https://archive.org/details/nauwkeurigebesch00bosm_0 |quote=RIO FORMOSA Anders gesegt DE BENIN. |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> In his description, Nyendael states the following about the character of the Benin people:\n\n''The inhabitants of the Benin are in general a kind and polite people, of whom one with kindness might get everything he desires. Whatever might be offered to them out of politeness, will always be doubled in return. However, they want their politeness to be returned with likewise courtesy as well, without the appearance of any disappointment or rudeness, and rightly so. To be sure, trying to take anything from them with force or violence, would be as if one tries to reach out to the [[Moon]] and will never be left unreckoned. When it comes to trade, they are very strict and will not suffer the slightest infringement of their customs, not even a [[Iota|iota]] can be changed. Though, when one is willing to accept these customs, they are very easy-going and will cooperate in every way possible to reach an agreement.''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bosman |first1=Willem |title=Nauwkeurige beschryving van de Guinese goud-, tand en slave-kust |date=1704 |publisher=Anthony Schouten |location=Utrecht |pages=[https://archive.org/details/nauwkeurigebesch00bosm_0/page/222 222]-223 |url=https://archive.org/details/nauwkeurigebesch00bosm_0 |quote=de maen. |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nGiven this characterization of the Benin culture, it might be understood that the Oba did not accept any colonial aspirations. As soon as the Oba began to suspect Britain of larger colonial designs, it ceased communications with them until the [[Benin Expedition of 1897|British Expedition in 1896-97]], when troops of that country captured, burned, and looted Benin City as part of a punitive mission, which brought the kingdom's imperial era to an end.<ref>Chapter 77, [[A History of the World in 100 Objects]]</ref>\n\n==Military==\nMilitary operations relied on a well trained disciplined force.<ref name=\"Osadolor\">{{cite web |last=Osadolor |first=Osarhieme Benson |title=The military system of Benin Kingdom, c. 1440\u20131897 (D) |url=http://ediss.sub.uni-hamburg.de/volltexte/2001/544/pdf/abstract.pdf |publisher=University of Hamburg |date=23 July 2001 |pages=4\u2013264}}</ref> At the head of the host stood the [[Oba of Benin]]. The monarch of the realm served as supreme military commander. Beneath him were subordinate generalissimos, the ''Ezomo'', the ''Iyase'', and others who supervised a Metropolitan Regiment based in the capital, and a Royal Regiment made up of hand-picked warriors that also served as bodyguards. Benin's Queen Mother also retained her own regiment, the \"Queen's Own\". The Metropolitan and Royal regiments were relatively stable semi-permanent or permanent formations. The Village Regiments provided the bulk of the fighting force and were mobilized as needed, sending contingents of warriors upon the command of the king and his generals. Formations were broken down into sub-units under designated commanders. Foreign observers often commented favorably on Benin's discipline and organization as \"better disciplined than any other Guinea nation\", contrasting them with the slacker troops from the Gold Coast.<ref>Robert Sydney Smith, Warfare & diplomacy in pre-colonial West Africa, [[University of Wisconsin Press]]: 1989, pp. 54\u201362</ref>\n\nUntil the introduction of guns in the 15th century, traditional weapons like the spear, short sword, and bow held sway. Efforts were made to reorganize a local guild of blacksmiths in the 18th century to manufacture light firearms, but dependence on imports was still heavy. Before the coming of the gun, guilds of blacksmiths were charged with war production\u2014particularly swords and iron spearheads.<ref name=\"Osadolor\"/>\n\nBenin's tactics were well organized, with preliminary plans weighed by the Oba and his sub-commanders. Logistics were organized to support missions from the usual porter forces, water transport via canoe, and requisitioning from localities the army passed through. Movement of troops via canoes was critically important in the lagoons, creeks and rivers of the Niger Delta, a key area of Benin's domination. Tactics in the field seem to have evolved over time. While the head-on clash was well known, documentation from the 18th century shows greater emphasis on avoiding continuous battle lines, and more effort to encircle an enemy (''ifianyako'').<ref name=\"Osadolor\"/>\n\nFortifications were important in the region and numerous military campaigns fought by Benin's soldiers revolved around sieges. As noted above, Benin's military earthworks are the largest of such structures in the world, and Benin's rivals also built extensively. Barring a successful assault, most sieges were resolved by a strategy of attrition, slowly cutting off and starving out the enemy fortification until it capitulated. On occasion, however, European mercenaries were called on to aid with these sieges. In 1603\u201304 for example, European cannon helped batter and destroy the gates of a town near present-day Lagos, allowing 10,000 warriors of Benin to enter and conquer it. As payment, the Europeans received items, such as palm oil and bundles of pepper.<ref>R.S. Smith, Warfare & diplomacy pp. 54\u201362</ref> The example of Benin shows the power of indigenous military systems, but also the role outside influences and new technologies brought to bear. This is a normal pattern among many nations\n\n===Britain seeks control over trade===\nBenin began to decline after 1700. Benin's power and wealth was continuously flourishing in the 19th century with the development of the trade in palm oil, textiles, ivory, slaves, and other resources. To preserve the kingdom's independence, bit by bit the Oba banned the export of goods from Benin, until the trade was exclusively in palm oil.\n\nBy the last half of the 19th century Great Britain had come to want a closer relationship with the Kingdom of Benin; for British officials were increasingly interested in controlling trade in the area and in accessing the kingdom's rubber resources to support their own growing tire market.\n\nSeveral attempts were made to achieve this end beginning with the official visit of [[Richard Francis Burton]] in 1862 when he was consul at [[Fernando P\u00f3 (island)|Fernando P\u00f3]]. Following that came attempts to establish a treaty between Benin and the United Kingdom by Hewtt, Blair and Annesley in 1884, 1885 and 1886 respectively. However, these efforts did not yield any results. The kingdom resisted becoming a British protectorate throughout the 1880s, but the British remained persistent. Progress was made finally in 1892 during the visit of Vice-Consul [[Henry Galway]]. This mission was the first official visit after Burton's. Moreover, it would also set in motion the events to come that would lead to Oba Ovonramwen's demise.\n\n===The Galway Treaty of 1892===\n\nAt the end of the 19th century, the Kingdom of Benin had managed to retain its independence and the Oba exercised a monopoly over trade which the British found irksome. The territory was coveted by an influential group of investors for its rich natural resources such as palm-oil, rubber and ivory. After British consul Richard Burton visited Benin in 1862 he wrote of Benin's as a place of \"gratuitous barbarity which stinks of death\", a narrative which was widely publicized in Britain and increased pressure for the territory's subjugation.{{sfn|Igbafe|1970|p=385}}\nIn spite of this pressure, the kingdom maintained independence and was not visited by another representative of Britain until 1892 when [[Henry Galway|Henry Gallwey]], the British Vice-Consul of Oil Rivers Protectorate (later [[Niger Coast Protectorate]]), visited Benin City hoping to open up trade and ultimately annex Benin Kingdom and make it a [[British protectorate]].{{sfn|Igbafe|1970|pp=385-400}}  Gallwey was able to get Omo n\u2019Oba ([[Ovonramwen]]) and his chiefs to sign a treaty which gave Britain legal justification for exerting greater influence over the Empire.  While the treaty itself contains text suggesting Ovonramwen actively sought Britain's protection, this appears to be a fiction. Gallway's own account suggests the Oba was hesitant to sign the treaty.{{sfn|Igbafe|1970}} Although some suggest that humanitarian motivations were driving Britain's actions,<ref>E.G. Hernon, A. Britain's Forgotton Wars, p.409 (2002)</ref> letters written between administrators suggest that economic motivations were predominant.{{sfn|Igbafe|1970|p=387}}  The treaty itself does not explicitly mention anything about Benin's \"bloody customs\" that Burton had written about, and instead only includes a vague clause about ensuring \"the general progress of civilization\".{{sfn|Igbafe|1970|p=387}}\n\n===The conflict of 1897===\n{{Main|Benin Expedition of 1897}}\n\n[[File:Flag of the Benin Empire.svg|thumb|An unidentified [[West African flag]] allegedly brought to Britain by Admiral F. W. Kennedy after the expedition.]]\n\nWhen people in Benin discovered Britain's true intentions were an invasion to depose the king of Benin, without approval from the king his generals ordered a preemptive attack on the British party approaching Benin City, including eight unknowing British representatives, who were killed. A [[Benin Expedition of 1897|punitive expedition]] was launched in 1897. The British force, under the command of Admiral Sir [[Harry Rawson]], razed and burned the city, destroying much of the country's treasured art and dispersing nearly all that remained. The stolen portrait figures, busts, and groups created in iron, carved ivory, and especially in brass (conventionally called the \"[[Benin Bronzes]]\") are now displayed in museums around the world.\n\n==Benin today==\nThe monarchy continues to exist today as one of the [[List of Nigerian traditional states|traditional states]] of contemporary Nigeria. [[Ewuare II]], the present king, is one of the most prominent of the various [[Nigerian traditional rulers|traditional rulers of Nigeria]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[[Edo people]]\n*[[Edo language]]\n*[[Festac Town]]\n*[[History of Nigeria]]\n*[[Walls of Benin]]\n*[[Flag of the Kingdom of Benin]]\n* [[Ancient Kano City Walls]] \n* [[Sungbo's Eredo]]\n* [[Oba of Benin]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n* [http://www.beninmoatfoundation.org.ng/ The Benin Moat Foundation] \n{{Archaeological sites in Nigeria}}\n{{coord missing|Nigeria}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:City walls|Benin]]\n[[Category:Walls]]\n[[Category:African architecture]]\n[[Category:Fortifications in Africa]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric Africa]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Historic buildings and structures in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Linear earthworks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n;Sources \n*{{cite journal| last=Igbafe | first=Philip A.| year=1970 | title=The fall of Benin: a reassessment | journal= Journal of African History | volume=11 | issue=3 |pages=385\u2013400 | doi=10.1017/S0021853700010215 | jstor=180345 | ref=harv }}\n* European traders in Benin to Major Copland Crawford. Reporting the stoppage of trade by the Benin King 1896 Apr 13, ''Catalogue of the Correspondence and Papers of the Niger Coast Protectorate'', 268 3/3/3, p.&nbsp;240. National Archives of Nigeria Enugu.\n* Sir Ralph Moore to Foreign Office. Reporting on the abortive Expedition into Benin. 1895 Sept.12 ''Catalogue of the Correspondence and Papers of the Niger Coast Protectorate'', 268 3/3/3, p.&nbsp;240. [[National Archives of Nigeria]] Enugu\n* J.R. Phillips to Foreign Office. Advising the deposition of the Benin King. 17 Nov 1896. Despatches to Foreign Office from Consul-General, ''Catalogue of the Correspondence and Papers of the Niger Coast Protectorate'', 268 3/3/3, p.&nbsp;240. National Archives of Nigeria Enugu.\n* Akenzua, Edun (2000). \"The Case of Benin\". Appendices to the Minutes of Evidence, Appendix 21, House of Commons, The United Kingdom Parliament, March 2000.\n* Ben-Amos, Paula Girshick (1999). Art, Innovation, and Politics in Eighteenth-Century Benin. Indiana University Press, 1999. {{ISBN|0-253-33503-5}}.\n*{{ cite book | last=Boisragon | first=Alan | author-link=Alan Boisragon | year=1897 | title=The Benin Massacre | place=London | publisher=Methuen | url=https://archive.org/details/beninmassacre00bois | ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal | last=Graham | first=James D. | year=1965 | title=The slave trade, depopulation and human sacrifice in Benin history: the general approach | journal=Cahiers d'\u00c9tudes africaines | volume=5 | issue=18 | pages=317\u2013334 | jstor=4390897 | ref=harv| doi=10.3406/cea.1965.3035 }}*{{cite book | last=Strayer | first=Robert W. | title=Ways of the World: A Brief Global History with Sources | location=New York | publisher=Bedford/St.Martin's | year=2013 | edition=2nd | isbn=978-0312583460 | ref=harv }}\n*{{ cite journal | last=Bondarenko | first=Dmitri M. | author-link=Dmitri Bondarenko | year=2005 | title=A homoarchic alternative to the homoarchic state: Benin Kingdom of the 13th\u201319th centuries | journal=Social Evolution & History | volume=4 | issue=2 | pages=18\u201388 | url=http://www.sociostudies.org/journal/articles/140520/ }}\n*{{ cite journal | last=Bondarenko  | first=Dmitri M. | year=2015 | title=The Benin Kingdom (13th \u2013 19th centuries) as a megacommunity | journal=Social Evolution & History | volume=14 | issue=2 | pages=46\u201376 | url=http://www.sociostudies.org/journal/articles/363729/ }}\n*{{cite book | last=Ezra | first=Kate | title=Royal Art of Benin: the Perls Collection in the Metropolitan Museum of Art | url=https://archive.org/details/royalartofbeninp0000ezra | location=New York | publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art | year=1992 | isbn=9780870996320 | url-access=registration }}\n*{{ cite book | last1=Roese | first1=P.M. | last2=Bondarenko | first2=D. M. | year=2003 | title=A Popular History of Benin. The Rise and Fall of a Mighty Forest Kingdom | place=Frankfurt am Main | publisher=Peter Lang | isbn=9780820460796 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{ cite book | last=Egharevba | first=Jacob U. | author-link=Jacob U. Egharevba  | year=1968 | title=Short History of Benin | place=Ibadan | publisher=Ibadan Up | oclc=1037105916 }}\n*{{ cite journal | last=Eisenhofer | first=Stefan | year=1995 | title=The origins of the Benin kingship in the works of Jacob Egharevba | journal=History in Africa | volume=22 | issue= | pages=141\u2013163 | jstor=3171912 | doi=10.2307/3171912 }}\n*{{ cite journal | last=Eisenhofer | first=Stefan | year=1997 | title=The Benin kinglist/s: some questions of chronology | journal=History in Africa | volume=24 | pages=139\u2013156 | jstor=3172022 | doi=10.2307/3172022 }}\n*{{cite journal | last=Graham | first=James D. | year=1965 | title=The slave trade, depopulation and human sacrifice in Benin history: the general approach | journal=Cahiers d'\u00c9tudes africaines | volume=5 | issue=18 | pages=317\u2013334 | jstor=4390897 | doi=10.3406/cea.1965.3035 }}\n*{{ cite book | last=Igbafe | first=Philip Aigbona | year=1979 | title=Benin Under British Administration: The Impact of Colonial Rule on an African Kingdom, 1897-1938 | place=London | publisher=Longman | oclc=473877102 }}\n*{{ cite journal | last=Palisot-Beauvois | first=A. | author-link=Palisot de Beauvois | year=1800 | title=Notice sur le peuple de B\u00e9nin  | language=French | journal=D\u00e9cade Philosophique | volume=2e Trimestre | issue=12 | pages=141\u2013151 | url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=JHxlAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA141 }} <!-- also available from Gallica: https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k4239892/f147.image -->\n*{{ cite book | last=Ryder | first=Alan Frederick Charles  | year= | title=Benin and the Europeans, (1485\u20131897) | place=London | publisher=Longmans | oclc=959073935 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.uq.net.au/~zzhsoszy/states/nigeria/edo.html Edo at Genealogical Gleanings]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/africa/features/storyofafrica/4chapter7.shtml The Story of Africa: Ife and Benin &mdash; BBC World Service]\n* [http://www.edoworld.net/origin_of_the_Edo_people.html The origin of Edos/Binis {source Edoworld}]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090917223644/http://deposit.ddb.de/cgi-bin/dokserv?idn=964084686&dok_var=d1&dok_ext=pdf&filename=964084686.pdf THE MILITARY SYSTEM OF BENIN KINGDOM, c.&nbsp;1440\u20131897]\n* Nimmons, Fidelia (2012) [http://iyiomonworks.blogspot.com/ Kingdom of Benin Blogs: Fiction, Myths and Lies]\n* The Metropolitan Museum of Art - [http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/pwmn_3/hd_pwmn_3.htm Idia: The First Queen Mother of Benin]\n\n{{Nigeria topics}}\n\n{{coord |6|20|N|5|37|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Kingdom of Benin|*]]\n[[Category:Edo people]]\n[[Category:Former monarchies of Africa]]\n[[Category:History of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Countries in precolonial Africa]]\n[[Category:Nigerian traditional states]]\n[[Category:French West Africa]]\n[[Category:Countries in medieval Africa]]\n[[Category:12th century in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:13th century in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:14th century in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:15th century in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:16th century in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:17th century in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:18th century in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:19th century in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1180]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1897]]\n[[Category:1180s establishments]]\n[[Category:1897 disestablishments in Africa]]\n[[Category:12th-century establishments in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:1890s disestablishments in Nigeria]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|native_name         = ''Edo''\n|conventional_long_name = Kingdom of Benin\n|common_name         = Benin Kingdom\n|country             = \n|era                 = \n|status              = \n|status_text         = \n|government_type     = [[Monarchy]]\n|year_start          = 1180\n|year_end            = 1897\n|event_start         = \n|date_start          = \n|event_end           = Annexed by the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n|date_end            = \n|p1                  = Igodomigodo\n|flag_p1             = Transparent_flag_with_question_mark.png\n|s1                  = Southern Nigeria Protectorate\n|flag_s1             = Flag of the Southern Nigeria Protectorate (1900\u20131914).svg\n|image_map           = Benin 1625 locator.png\n|image_map_caption   = The extent of Benin in 1625\n|capital             = Edo<br/>(now [[Benin City]])\n|common_languages    = [[Edo language|Edo]]\n|religion            = \n|currency            = \n|leader1             = Eweka I <ref>Ben-Amos, Paula Girshick (1995). The Art of Benin Revised Edition. British Museum Press. p. 20. {{ISBN|0-7141-2520-2}}.</ref>\n|leader2             = [[Ewuare]] (1440\u20131473)\n|leader3             = [[Ovonramwen]] (exile 1897)\n|leader4             = [[Erediauwa I]] (post-imperial)\n|leader5             = [[Ewuare II]] (post-imperial)\n|year_leader1        = 1180\u20131246\n|year_leader2        = 1440\u20131473\n|year_leader4        = 1978\u20132016\n|year_leader5        = 2016-\n|title_leader        = [[Oba of Benin#List of Obas of the Benin Empire (1180-present)|King/Emperor (Oba)]]\n|<!-- Area and population of a given year -->\n|stat_year1          = 1625\n|stat_area1          = 90000\n|stat_pop1           = \n|today               = {{flag|Nigeria}}\n|demonym=|area_km2=|area_rank=|GDP_PPP=|GDP_PPP_year=|HDI=|HDI_year=}}\n\nThe '''Kingdom of Benin''', also known as the '''Benin Kingdom''', was a pre-[[Colonisation of Africa|colonial]] kingdom in what is now southern [[Nigeria]]. It is not to be confused with [[Benin]], the post-colonial nation state. The Kingdom of Benin's capital was Edo, now known as [[Benin City]] in [[Edo State|Edo state]]. The Benin Kingdom was \"one of the oldest and most highly developed states in the coastal hinterland of [[West Africa]], dating perhaps to the eleventh century CE\",{{sfn|Strayer|2013|pp=695-696}} until it was annexed by the [[British Empire]] in 1897.\n\n==Oral traditions==\n\nThe original people and founders of the Benin Kingdom, the [[Edo people]], were initially ruled by the [[List of the Ogiso|Ogiso]] (Kings of the Sky) who called their land [[Igodomigodo]]. The first Ogiso (Ogiso Igodo), wielded much influence and gained popularity as a good ruler. He died after a long reign and was succeeded by Ere, his eldest son. In the 12th century, a great [[palace]] intrigue erupted and crown prince Ekaladerhan, the only son of the last Ogiso, was sentenced to death as a result of the first queen (who was barren) deliberately changing an oracle's message to the Ogiso. In carrying out the royal order that he be killed, the palace messengers had mercy and set the prince free at [[Ughoton]] near Benin. When his father the Ogiso died, the Ogiso dynasty officially ended. The people and royal kingmakers preferred their late king's son as the next to rule.\n\nThe exiled Prince Ekaladerhan had by this time changed his name to Izoduwa (meaning 'I have chosen the path of prosperity') and found his way to [[Ile-Ife]]. It was during this period of confusion in Benin that the elders, led by Chief Oliha, mounted a search for the banished Prince Ekaladerhan - whom the Ife people now called [[Oduduwa]]. Oduduwa, who could not return due to his advanced age, granted them Oranmiyan, his grandson, to rule over them. Oranmiyan was resisted by Ogiamien Irebor, one of the palace chiefs, and took up his abode in the palace built for him at Usama by the elders (now a [[coronation]] [[shrine]]). Soon after his arrival, he married a beautiful lady, Erinmwinde, daughter of Ogie-Egor, the ninth Enogie of Egor, by whom he had a son. After residing there for some years he called a meeting of the people and renounced his office, remarking in vexation ''Ile-Ibinu'' (\"ile\" means land, \"binu\" mean anger, and thus the kingdom was called Ibinu, which was mispronounced Bini in the 15th and 16th centuries by the Portuguese). This was out of frustration as he often expressed that \"only a child born, trained and educated in the arts and mysteries of the land could reign over the people\". He arranged for his son born to him by Erinmwinde, Eweka, to be made king in his place, and returned to Yorubaland thereafter. His son the new king was soon found to be deaf and dumb, and so the elders appealed to Oranmiyan. He gave them charmed seeds known as \"omo ayo\" to play with, saying that to do so will make him talk. The little Eweka played with the seeds with his peers at Egor, his mother's hometown. While playing with the seeds, he announced \"Owomika\" as his royal name. Thus, he gave rise to the tradition of the subsequent Obas of Benin spending seven days and nights at Usama before proceeding to announce their royal names at Egor. Eweka thus started a dynasty that now bears his name. Oranmiyan went on to serve as the founder of the [[Oyo Empire]], where he ruled as the first [[Alaafin]] of Oyo. His descendants now rule in Ile Ife, Oyo and Benin.\n\nBy the 15th century, Benin had expanded into a thriving city-state. The twelfth Oba in the line, Oba [[Ewuare|Ewuare the Great]] (1440\u20131473) would expand the [[city-state]]'s territories to surrounding regions.\n\nIt was not until the 15th century, during the reign of Oba Ewuare the Great, that the kingdom's administrative centre, the city of Ubinu (or Ibinu), began to be known as [[Benin City]] by the [[Portugal|Portuguese]], a pronunciation later adopted by the locals as well. The Portuguese would write this down as Benin City. Edo's neighbours, such as the Itsekiris and the Urhobos, continued to refer to the city as Ubini up until the late 19th century.\n\nAside from Benin City, the system of rule of the Oba in the empire, even through the golden age of the kingdom, was still loosely based upon the Ogiso dynasty's tradition, which was military protection in exchange for pledged allegiance and taxes paid to the royal administrative centre. The language and culture was not enforced, as the empire remained heterogeneous and localized according to each group within the kingdom, though a local enogie (or duke) was often appointed by the Oba for specific ethnic areas.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Early history ===\nBy the 1st century BCE, the Benin territory was partially agricultural; and it became primarily agricultural by around 500 CE, but hunting and gathering still remained important. Also by 500 CE, [[iron]] was in use by the inhabitants of the Benin territory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bondarenko|first=Dmitri|last2=Roese|first2=Peter|date=1999-01-01|title=Benin Prehistory. The Origin and Settling Down of the Edo|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/283567896_Benin_Prehistory_The_Origin_and_Settling_Down_of_the_Edo|journal=Anthropos: International Review of Anthropology and Linguistics|volume=94|pages=542\u2013552}}</ref>\n\nBenin City (formerly Edo) sprang up by around 1000 CE, in a forest that could be easily defended. The dense vegetation and narrow paths made the city easy to defend against attacks. The [[rainforest]], which Benin City is situated in, helped in the development of the city because of its vast resources \u2014 fish from rivers and creeks, animals to hunt, leaves for roofing, plants for medicine, ivory for carving and trading, and wood for boat building \u2014 that could be exploited. However, domesticated animals, from the forest and surrounding areas, could not survive, due to a disease spread by [[Tsetse fly|tsetse flies]]; after centuries of exposure, some animals, such as cattle and goat, developed a resistance to the disease.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Forgotten Africa: An Introduction to Its Archaeology|last=Connah|first=Graham|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|isbn=978-0415305914|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/forgottenafricai00grah/page/125 125-6]|url=https://archive.org/details/forgottenafricai00grah/page/125}}</ref>\n\nThe original name of the Benin Kingdom, at its creation some time in the first millennium [[Common Era|CE]], was [[Igodomigodo]], as its inhabitants called it. Their ruler was called [[Ogiso]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Cahoon |url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Nigeria_native.html |title=Nigerian Traditional States |website=Worldstatesmen.org |date= |accessdate=2016-11-17}}</ref> Nearly 36 known Ogiso are accounted for as rulers of this initial incarnation of the state.\n\n{{short description|Series of earthworks around present-day Benin City, Nigeria}}\n[[File:Ancient_Benin_city.JPG|thumb|Depiction of [[Benin City]] of 1668. In the center there is a wall like structure, which probably are the walls of Benin.]]\nThe '''Walls of Benin''' are a series of [[Earthworks (archaeology)|earthworks]] made up of banks and ditches, called ''{{font|I|font=serif}}ya'' in the [[Edo language]] in the area around present-day [[Benin City]], the capital of present-day [[Edo State|Edo]], [[Nigeria]]. They consist of {{convert|15|km|abbr=off}} of city iya  and an estimated {{convert|16000|km|abbr=off}}  in the rural area around Benin.<ref name=\"Protection\">{{cite book |author1=Patrick Darling |editor1-last=Korka |editor1-first=Elena |title=The Protection of Archaeological Heritage in Times of Economic Crisis |date=2015 |publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing |isbn=9781443874113 |page=341\u2013352 |chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B_imBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA353&dq=Walls+of+Benin+%22Patrick+Darling%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiis5CU_fTgAhUsShUIHRhaC7UQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=Walls%20of%20Benin%20&f=false |accessdate=9 March 2019 |language=en |chapter=Conservation Management of the Benin Earthworks of Southern Nigeria: A critical review of past and present action plans}}</ref> Some estimates suggest that the walls of Benin may have been constructed between the thirteenth and mid-fifteenth century CE<ref name=\"Ogundiran\">{{cite journal |last1=Ogundiran |first1=Akinwumi |title=Four Millennia of Cultural History in Nigeria (ca. 2000 B.C.\u2013A.D. 1900): Archaeological Perspectives |journal=Journal of World Prehistory |date=June 2005 |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=133\u2013168|doi=10.1007/s10963-006-9003-y }}</ref> and others suggest that the walls of Benin (in the Esan region) may have been constructed during the first millennium CE.<ref name=\"Ogundiran\"/><ref name=\"MacEachern\">{{cite journal |last1=MacEachern |first1=Scott |title=Two thousand years of West African history |url=https://www.academia.edu/831918 |journal=African Archaeology: A Critical Introduction |publisher=Academia}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== First Encounters and Records ===\nThe Benin City walls have been known to Westerners since around 1500. Around 1500, the Portuguese explorer [[Duarte Pacheco Pereira]], briefly described the walls during his travels. Another description given around 1600, one hundred years after Pereira's description, is by the Dutch explorer Dierick Ruiters.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|date=June 1967|journal=Journal of the Historical Society of Nigeria|volume=3|issue=4|pages=597\u2013599|issn=0018-2540|jstor=41856902|title=New Light on the Benin City Walls}}</ref>\n\nPereira's account of the walls is as follows: \n\n{{quote|This city is about a [[League (unit)|league]] long from gate to gate; it has no wall but is surrounded by a large moat, very wide and deep, which suffices for its defence.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nigerian Perspectives: An Historical Anthology|last=Hodgkin|first=Thomas|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1960|isbn=978-0192154347|location=|pages=93}}</ref>}}\nThe [[Archaeology|archaeologist]] [[Graham Connah]] suggests that Pereira was mistaken with his description by saying that there was no wall. Connah says, \"[Pereira] considered that a bank of earth was not a wall in the sense of the Europe of his day.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRuiters' account of the walls is as follows:\n\n{{quote|At the gate where I entered on horseback, I saw a very high bulwark, very thick of earth, with a very deep broad ditch, but it was dry, and full of high trees... That gate is a reasonable good gate, made of wood in their manner, which is to be shut, and there always there is watch holden.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nigerian Perspectives: An Historical Anthology|last=Hodgkin|first=Thomas|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1960|isbn=978-0192154347|location=|pages=120}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Construction ===\nEstimates for the initial construction of the walls range from the first millennium CE to the mid-fifteenth century CE. According to Connah, oral tradition and travelers' accounts suggest a construction date of 1450-1500 CE.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|date=January 1972|title=Archaeology of Benin|journal=The Journal of African History|volume=13|issue=1|pages=33|doi=10.1017/S0021853700000244}}</ref> It has been estimated that, assuming a 10 hour work day, a labour force of 5,000 men could have completed the walls within 97 days, or by 2,421 men in 200 days. However, these estimates have been criticized for not taking into account the time it would have taken to extract earth from an ever deepening hole and the time it would have taken to heap the earth into a high bank.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Connah|first=Graham|date=June 1967|journal=Journal of the Historical Society of Nigeria|volume=3|issue=4|pages=608|issn=0018-2540|jstor=41856902|title=New Light on the Benin City Walls}}</ref> It is unknown whether slavery or some other type of labour was used in the construction of the walls.\n\n==Description==\n\nThe walls were built of a ditch and dike structure; the ditch dug to form an inner moat with the excavated earth used to form the exterior rampart.\n\nThe Benin Walls were ravaged by the British in 1897 during what has come to be called the ''[[Benin Expedition of 1897|Punitive expedition]]''. Scattered pieces of the structure remain in Edo, with the vast majority of them being used by the locals for building purposes. What remains of the wall itself continues to be torn down for real estate developments.<ref>http://www.beninmoatfoundation.org/clarioncall.html  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725061950/http://www.beninmoatfoundation.org/clarioncall.html |date=July 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n[[Fred Pearce]] wrote in New Scientist:\n<div>{{quote|They extend for some 16,000&nbsp;km in all, in a mosaic of more than 500 interconnected settlement boundaries. They cover 2,510 sq. miles (6,500 square kilometres) and were all dug by the [[Edo State|Edo]] people. In all, they are four times longer than the [[Great Wall of China]], and consumed a hundred times more material than the [[Great Pyramid of Cheops]]. They took an estimated 150 million hours of digging to construct, and are perhaps the largest single archaeological phenomenon on the planet.<ref name=\"African Queen\">Pearce, Fred. [https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg16322035.100-the-african-queen.html?page=2 ''African Queen'']. New Scientist, 11 September 1999, Issue 2203.</ref>}}</div>\n<div>\n[[Ethnomathematics|Ethnomathematician]]  [[Ron Eglash]] has discussed the planned layout of the city using [[fractals]] as the basis, not only in the city itself and the villages but even in the rooms of houses. He commented that \"When Europeans first came to Africa, they considered the architecture very disorganised and thus primitive. It never occurred to them that the Africans might have been using a form of mathematics that they hadn\u2019t even discovered yet.\"<ref name=\"Koutonin\">{{cite news|last1=Koutonin|first1=Mawuna|title=Story of cities #5: Benin City, the mighty medieval capital now lost without trace|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2016/mar/18/story-of-cities-5-benin-city-edo-nigeria-mighty-medieval-capital-lost-without-trace|accessdate=2 April 2018|date=18 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"250px\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Ancient Benin city.JPG|[[Benin city]] in the 17th century.\nFile:Drawing of Benin City made by an English officer 1897.jpg|Benin in 1897\n</gallery>\n\n=== Later history ===\nExcavations at Benin City have revealed that it was already flourishing around 1200-1300 CE.<ref name=\":0a\">{{Cite book|title=The Cambridge History of Africa, Volume 3: From c.1050 to c.1600|last=Oliver|first=Roland|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1977|isbn=978-0521209816|location=|pages=476}}</ref>\n\nIn 1440, [[Oba Ewuare]], also known as Ewuare the Great, came to power and expanded the borders of the former city-state. It was only at this time that the administrative centre of the kingdom began to be referred to as Ubinu after the [[Yoruba language|Portuguese]]<nowiki/> word and corrupted to Bini by the [[Itsekhiri]], [[Urhobo people|Urhobo]] and Edo who all lived together in the royal administrative centre of the kingdom. The Portuguese who arrived in an expedition led by Joao Afonso de Aveiro in 1485 would refer to it as Benin and the centre would become known as Benin City.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nThe Kingdom of Benin eventually gained political strength and ascendancy over much of what is now mid-western Nigeria.\n\nBy the seventeenth century CE, the Kingdom began to decline. Multiple civil wars broke out and disputes over the kingship took place.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Kingdom of Benin in West Africa|last=Millar|first=Heather|publisher=Benchmark Books|year=1996|isbn=978-0761400882|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kingdomofbeninin00mill/page/14 14]|url=https://archive.org/details/kingdomofbeninin00mill/page/14}}</ref>\n\n==Rituals and Law==\n\n=== Human Sacrifice ===\nForty-one female skeletons thrown into a pit were discovered by the [[archaeologist]] [[Graham Connah]]. These findings indicate that [[human sacrifice]] took place in Benin City since the thirteenth century CE.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Understanding Early Civilizations: A Comparative Study|last=Trigger|first=Bruce G.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-521-822459|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/479 479]|oclc=50291226|url=https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/479}}</ref> From the early days, human sacrifices were a part of the state religion. But many of the sensationalist accounts of the sacrifices, says [[historian]] J.D. Graham, are largely exaggerated or based on rumour and speculation. He says that all of the evidence \"points to a limited, ritual custom of human sacrifice.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Graham|first=James D.|date=1965|title=The Slave Trade, Depopulation and Human Sacrifice in Benin History: The General Approach|journal=Cahiers d'\u00c9tudes Africaines|volume=5|issue=18|pages=327\u201330|jstor=4390897}}</ref>\n\nHumans were sacrificed in an annual ritual in honour of the god of iron, where warriors from Benin City would perform an acrobatic dance while suspended from the trees. The ritual recalled a mythical war against the sky.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=The Benin Kingdom and the Edo-speaking Peoples of South-western Nigeria|last=Bradbury|first=R.E.|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=978-1315293837|location=|pages=54\u20138}}</ref>\n\nSacrifices of a man, a woman, a goat, a cow and a ram were also made to a god quite literally called \"the king of death.\" The god, named Ogiuwu, was worshipped at a special altar in the centre of Benin City.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThere were two separate annual series of rites that honoured past Obas. Sacrifices were performed every fifth day. At the end of each series of rites, the current Oba's own father was honoured with a public festival. During the festival, twelve criminals, chosen from a prison where the worst criminals were held, were sacrificed.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nBy the end of the eighteenth century, three to four people were sacrificed at the mouth of the Benin River annually, to attract European trade.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Law|first=Robin|date=January 1985|title=Human Sacrifice in Pre-Colonial West Africa|journal=African Affairs|volume=84|issue=334|pages=65|jstor=722523}}</ref>\n\nAt the burial rituals of Obas, human sacrifice was present; bodyguards of the Oba include those sacrificed. Additionally, wives and slaves of the Oba committed suicide, so that they could continue serving him in the afterlife.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Understanding Early Civilizations: A Comparative Study|last=Trigger|first=Bruce G.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2003|isbn=978-0-521-822459|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/88 88]|url=https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/88}}</ref>\n\n=== Burials ===\nThe monarchy of Benin was [[Hereditary monarchy|hereditary]]; the eldest son was to become the new Oba. In order to validate the succession of the kingship, the eldest son had to bury his father and perform elaborate rituals. If the eldest son failed to complete these tasks, the eldest son might be disqualified from becoming king.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Understanding Early Civilizations: A Comparative Study|last=Trigger|first=Bruce G.|date=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-82245-9|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/77 77\u201378]|oclc=50291226|url=https://archive.org/details/understandingear0000trig/page/77}}</ref>\n\n=== Separation of son and mother ===\nAfter the son was installed as king, the mother was transferred to a [[palace]] just outside Benin City, in a place called Uselu. The mother held a considerable amount of power; she was, however, never allowed to meet her son \u2014 who was now divine ruler \u2014 again.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Divinity of the Oba===\nIn Benin, the Oba was seen as [[Divinity|divine]]. The Oba's divinity and sacredness was the focal point of the kingship. The Oba was shrouded in mystery; he only left his palace on ceremonial occasions. It was previously punishable by death to assert that the Oba performed human acts, such as eating, sleeping, dying, washing. The Oba was also credited with having magical powers.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Benin Kingdom and the Edo-speaking Peoples of South-western Nigeria|last=Bradbury|first=R.E.|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=978-1315293837|location=|pages=40}}</ref>\n\n==Golden Age==\nThe Oba had become the mount of power within the region. Oba Ewuare, the first ''Golden Age'' Oba, is credited with turning Benin City into a city-state from a military fortress built by the Ogisos, protected by moats and walls. It was from this bastion that he launched his military campaigns and began the expansion of the kingdom from the Edo-speaking heartlands.\n\nA series of walls marked the incremental growth of the sacred city from 850 AD until its decline in the 16th century. To enclose his palace he commanded the building of Benin's inner wall, an {{convert|7|mi|km|order=flip|adj=mid|-long|0}} earthen rampart girded by a moat {{convert|20|ft|m|order=flip|0|abbr=on}} deep. This was excavated in the early 1960s by [[Graham Connah]]. Connah estimated that its construction if spread out over five dry seasons, would have required a workforce of 1,000 laborers working ten hours a day seven days a week. Ewuare also added great thoroughfares and erected nine fortified gateways.\n\nExcavations also uncovered a rural network of earthen walls {{convert|4000|to|8000|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on|-3}} long that would have taken an estimated 150 million man-hours to build and must have taken hundreds of years to build. These were apparently raised to mark out territories for towns and cities. Thirteen years after Ewuare's death, tales of Benin's splendors lured more Portuguese traders to the city gates.<ref>Time Life Lost Civilizations series: Africa's Glorious Legacy (1994) pp.&nbsp;102\u20134</ref>\n\nAt its height, Benin dominated trade along the entire coastline from the Western Niger Delta, through Lagos to the kingdom of Great Accra (modern-day Ghana).<ref>{{cite book |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=ZPnDBAAAQBAJ |page=152 }} |title=The History of Africa: The Quest for Eternal Harmony }}</ref> It was for this reason that this coastline was named the [[Bight of Benin]]. The present-day Republic of Benin, formerly Dahomey, decided to choose the name of this bight as the name of its country. Benin ruled over the tribes of the Niger Delta including the Western Igbo, Ijaw, Itshekiri, Ika, Isoko and Urhobo amongst others. It also held sway over the Eastern Yoruba tribes of Ondo, Ekiti, Mahin/Ugbo, and Ijebu.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=B5QuAQAAIAAJ&q=orhogbua+portugal&dq=orhogbua+portugal |title=The Benin City Pilgrimage Stations |isbn=9789783153356 |last1=Aisien |first1=Ekhaguosa |year=2001 }}</ref> It also conquered what eventually became the city of [[Lagos]] hundreds of years before the British took over in 1851.<ref>{{cite book |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=MCHSd62Tse8C |page=27 }} |title=Slavery and the Birth of an African City: Lagos, 1760--1900 }}</ref>\n\nThe state developed an advanced artistic culture, especially in its famous artifacts of bronze, iron and ivory. These include bronze wall plaques and life-sized bronze heads depicting the Obas and Iyobas of Benin. The most well-known artifact is based on [[Queen Idia]], now best known as the ''[[Benin ivory mask|FESTAC Mask]]'' after its use in 1977 in the logo of the Nigeria-financed and hosted Second Festival of Black & African Arts and Culture (FESTAC 77).\n\n==European contact==\nBefore trade and contact with Europeans, supplies of metal were very scarce in Benin and writing was not present. After the Kingdom of Benin began trading with Europeans at the end of the 15th century CE, the quantity of [[bronze]] castings and thickness of casting had greatly increased; before trade with Europeans, the blades were incredibly thin and only wealthy elites could afford work with these metals that were regarded as precious.<ref name=\":0a\" /> Writing was not introduced to the Kingdom of Benin until the [[Niger Coast Protectorate|colonial period]] \u2014 near the end of the 19th century CE.<ref>Connah (2004), pp. 129</ref>\n\nThe first European travelers to reach Benin were [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] explorers under Jo\u00e3o Afonso de Aveiro in about 1485. A strong mercantile relationship developed, with the Edo trading slaves and tropical products such as [[ivory trade|ivory]], [[Black pepper|pepper]] and [[palm oil]] for European goods such as [[Manilla (money)|manillas]] and [[guns]]. In the early 16th century, the Oba sent an ambassador to [[Lisbon]], and the king of Portugal sent [[Christianity|Christian]] missionaries to Benin City. Some residents of Benin City could still speak a [[pidgin]] Portuguese in the late 19th century.\n\nThe first English expedition to Benin was in 1553, and significant trading developed between England and Benin based on the export of ivory, palm oil, pepper, and slaves. Visitors in the 16th and 19th centuries brought back to [[Europe]] tales of \"Great Benin\", a fabulous city of noble buildings, ruled over by a powerful king. This picture is for instance shown in [[Olfert Dapper]]'s [[Description of Africa (1668 book)|''Naukeurige beschrijvinge der Afrikaensche gewesten'']], published in [[Amsterdam]] in 1668.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dapper |first1=Olfert |title=Naukeurige beschrijvinge der Afrikaensche gewesten |date=1668 |publisher=[[Jacob van Meurs]] |location=Amsterdam |pages=[https://archive.org/details/gri_33125009359999/page/n676 495]-505 |url=https://archive.org/details/gri_33125009359999|quote=naukeurige beschrijvinge der afrikaensche gewesten. }}</ref> It states the following about the royal palace:\n\n''The king's court is square and located on the right-hand side of the city, as one enters it through the gate of Gotton. It is about the same size as the city of [[Haarlem]] and entirely surrounded by a special wall, comparable to the one which encircles the town. It is divided into many magnificent palaces, houses and apartments of the courtiers, and comprises beautiful and long squares with galleries, about as large as the [[Euronext Amsterdam|Exchange at Amsterdam]]. The buildings are of different sizes however, resting on wooden pillars, from top to bottom lined with copper casts, on which pictures of their war exploits and battles are engraved. All of them are being very well maintained. Most of the buildings within this court are covered with palm leaves, instead of with square planks, and every roof is adorned with a small spired tower, on which casted copper birds are standing, being very artfully sculpted and lifelike with their wings spread.''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dapper |first1=Olfert |title=Naukeurige beschrijvinge der Afrikaensche gewesten |date=1668 |publisher=Jacob van Meurs |location=Amsterdam |pages=[https://archive.org/details/gri_33125009359999/page/n676 495]-496 |url=https://archive.org/details/gri_33125009359999 |quote=495. |accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAnother Dutch traveler, [[David van Nyendael]], visited Benin in 1699 and also wrote an account of the kingdom. Nyendael's description was published in 1704 as an appendix to [[Willem Bosman]]'s ''Nauwkeurige beschryving van de Guinese goud-, tand- en slave-kust''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bosman |first1=Willem |title=Nauwkeurige beschryving van de Guinese goud-, tand- en slave-kust |date=1704 |publisher=Anthony Schouten |location=Utrecht |pages=[https://archive.org/details/nauwkeurigebesch00bosm_0/page/212 212]-257 |url=https://archive.org/details/nauwkeurigebesch00bosm_0 |quote=RIO FORMOSA Anders gesegt DE BENIN. |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> In his description, Nyendael states the following about the character of the Benin people:\n\n''The inhabitants of the Benin are in general a kind and polite people, of whom one with kindness might get everything he desires. Whatever might be offered to them out of politeness, will always be doubled in return. However, they want their politeness to be returned with likewise courtesy as well, without the appearance of any disappointment or rudeness, and rightly so. To be sure, trying to take anything from them with force or violence, would be as if one tries to reach out to the [[Moon]] and will never be left unreckoned. When it comes to trade, they are very strict and will not suffer the slightest infringement of their customs, not even a [[Iota|iota]] can be changed. Though, when one is willing to accept these customs, they are very easy-going and will cooperate in every way possible to reach an agreement.''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bosman |first1=Willem |title=Nauwkeurige beschryving van de Guinese goud-, tand en slave-kust |date=1704 |publisher=Anthony Schouten |location=Utrecht |pages=[https://archive.org/details/nauwkeurigebesch00bosm_0/page/222 222]-223 |url=https://archive.org/details/nauwkeurigebesch00bosm_0 |quote=de maen. |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nGiven this characterization of the Benin culture, it might be understood that the Oba did not accept any colonial aspirations. As soon as the Oba began to suspect Britain of larger colonial designs, it ceased communications with them until the [[Benin Expedition of 1897|British Expedition in 1896-97]], when troops of that country captured, burned, and looted Benin City as part of a punitive mission, which brought the kingdom's imperial era to an end.<ref>Chapter 77, [[A History of the World in 100 Objects]]</ref>\n\n==Military==\nMilitary operations relied on a well trained disciplined force.<ref name=\"Osadolor\">{{cite journal |last=Osadolor |first=Osarhieme Benson |title=The military system of Benin Kingdom, c. 1440\u20131897 (D) |url=http://ediss.sub.uni-hamburg.de/volltexte/2001/544/pdf/abstract.pdf |publisher=University of Hamburg |date=23 July 2001 |pages=4\u2013264}}</ref> At the head of the host stood the [[Oba of Benin]]. The monarch of the realm served as supreme military commander. Beneath him were subordinate generalissimos, the ''Ezomo'', the ''Iyase'', and others who supervised a Metropolitan Regiment based in the capital, and a Royal Regiment made up of hand-picked warriors that also served as bodyguards. Benin's Queen Mother also retained her own regiment, the \"Queen's Own\". The Metropolitan and Royal regiments were relatively stable semi-permanent or permanent formations. The Village Regiments provided the bulk of the fighting force and were mobilized as needed, sending contingents of warriors upon the command of the king and his generals. Formations were broken down into sub-units under designated commanders. Foreign observers often commented favorably on Benin's discipline and organization as \"better disciplined than any other Guinea nation\", contrasting them with the slacker troops from the Gold Coast.<ref>Robert Sydney Smith, Warfare & diplomacy in pre-colonial West Africa, [[University of Wisconsin Press]]: 1989, pp. 54\u201362</ref>\n\nUntil the introduction of guns in the 15th century, traditional weapons like the spear, short sword, and bow held sway. Efforts were made to reorganize a local guild of blacksmiths in the 18th century to manufacture light firearms, but dependence on imports was still heavy. Before the coming of the gun, guilds of blacksmiths were charged with war production\u2014particularly swords and iron spearheads.<ref name=\"Osadolor\"/>\n\nBenin's tactics were well organized, with preliminary plans weighed by the Oba and his sub-commanders. Logistics were organized to support missions from the usual porter forces, water transport via canoe, and requisitioning from localities the army passed through. Movement of troops via canoes was critically important in the lagoons, creeks and rivers of the Niger Delta, a key area of Benin's domination. Tactics in the field seem to have evolved over time. While the head-on clash was well known, documentation from the 18th century shows greater emphasis on avoiding continuous battle lines, and more effort to encircle an enemy (''ifianyako'').<ref name=\"Osadolor\"/>\n\nFortifications were important in the region and numerous military campaigns fought by Benin's soldiers revolved around sieges. As noted above, Benin's military earthworks are the largest of such structures in the world, and Benin's rivals also built extensively. Barring a successful assault, most sieges were resolved by a strategy of attrition, slowly cutting off and starving out the enemy fortification until it capitulated. On occasion, however, European mercenaries were called on to aid with these sieges. In 1603\u201304 for example, European cannon helped batter and destroy the gates of a town near present-day Lagos, allowing 10,000 warriors of Benin to enter and conquer it. As payment, the Europeans received items, such as palm oil and bundles of pepper.<ref>R.S. Smith, Warfare & diplomacy pp. 54\u201362</ref> The example of Benin shows the power of indigenous military systems, but also the role outside influences and new technologies brought to bear. This is a normal pattern among many nations\n\n===Britain seeks control over trade===\nBenin began to decline after 1700. Benin's power and wealth was continuously flourishing in the 19th century with the development of the trade in palm oil, textiles, ivory, slaves, and other resources. To preserve the kingdom's independence, bit by bit the Oba banned the export of goods from Benin, until the trade was exclusively in palm oil.\n\nBy the last half of the 19th century Great Britain had come to want a closer relationship with the Kingdom of Benin; for British officials were increasingly interested in controlling trade in the area and in accessing the kingdom's rubber resources to support their own growing tire market.\n\nSeveral attempts were made to achieve this end beginning with the official visit of [[Richard Francis Burton]] in 1862 when he was consul at [[Fernando P\u00f3 (island)|Fernando P\u00f3]]. Following that came attempts to establish a treaty between Benin and the United Kingdom by Hewtt, Blair and Annesley in 1884, 1885 and 1886 respectively. However, these efforts did not yield any results. The kingdom resisted becoming a British protectorate throughout the 1880s, but the British remained persistent. Progress was made finally in 1892 during the visit of Vice-Consul [[Henry Galway]]. This mission was the first official visit after Burton's. Moreover, it would also set in motion the events to come that would lead to Oba Ovonramwen's demise.\n\n===The Galway Treaty of 1892===\n\nAt the end of the 19th century, the Kingdom of Benin had managed to retain its independence and the Oba exercised a monopoly over trade which the British found irksome. The territory was coveted by an influential group of investors for its rich natural resources such as palm-oil, rubber and ivory. After British consul Richard Burton visited Benin in 1862 he wrote of Benin's as a place of \"gratuitous barbarity which stinks of death\", a narrative which was widely publicized in Britain and increased pressure for the territory's subjugation.{{sfn|Igbafe|1970|p=385}}\nIn spite of this pressure, the kingdom maintained independence and was not visited by another representative of Britain until 1892 when [[Henry Galway|Henry Gallwey]], the British Vice-Consul of Oil Rivers Protectorate (later [[Niger Coast Protectorate]]), visited Benin City hoping to open up trade and ultimately annex Benin Kingdom and make it a [[British protectorate]].{{sfn|Igbafe|1970|pp=385-400}}  Gallwey was able to get Omo n\u2019Oba ([[Ovonramwen]]) and his chiefs to sign a treaty which gave Britain legal justification for exerting greater influence over the Empire.  While the treaty itself contains text suggesting Ovonramwen actively sought Britain's protection, this appears to be a fiction. Gallway's own account suggests the Oba was hesitant to sign the treaty.{{sfn|Igbafe|1970}} Although some suggest that humanitarian motivations were driving Britain's actions,<ref>E.G. Hernon, A. Britain's Forgotton Wars, p.409 (2002)</ref> letters written between administrators suggest that economic motivations were predominant.{{sfn|Igbafe|1970|p=387}}  The treaty itself does not explicitly mention anything about Benin's \"bloody customs\" that Burton had written about, and instead only includes a vague clause about ensuring \"the general progress of civilization\".{{sfn|Igbafe|1970|p=387}}\n\n===The conflict of 1897===\n{{Main|Benin Expedition of 1897}}\n\n[[File:Flag of the Benin Empire.svg|thumb|An unidentified [[West African flag]] allegedly brought to Britain by Admiral F. W. Kennedy after the expedition.]]\n\nWhen people in Benin discovered Britain's true intentions were an invasion to depose the king of Benin, without approval from the king his generals ordered a preemptive attack on the British party approaching Benin City, including eight unknowing British representatives, who were killed. A [[Benin Expedition of 1897|punitive expedition]] was launched in 1897. The British force, under the command of Admiral Sir [[Harry Rawson]], razed and burned the city, destroying much of the country's treasured art and dispersing nearly all that remained. The stolen portrait figures, busts, and groups created in iron, carved ivory, and especially in brass (conventionally called the \"[[Benin Bronzes]]\") are now displayed in museums around the world.\n\n==Benin today==\nThe monarchy continues to exist today as one of the [[List of Nigerian traditional states|traditional states]] of contemporary Nigeria. [[Ewuare II]], the present king, is one of the most prominent of the various [[Nigerian traditional rulers|traditional rulers of Nigeria]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[[Edo people]]\n*[[Edo language]]\n*[[Festac Town]]\n*[[History of Nigeria]]\n*[[Walls of Benin]]\n*[[Flag of the Kingdom of Benin]]\n* [[Ancient Kano City Walls]] \n* [[Sungbo's Eredo]]\n* [[Oba of Benin]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n* [http://www.beninmoatfoundation.org.ng/ The Benin Moat Foundation] \n{{Archaeological sites in Nigeria}}\n{{coord missing|Nigeria}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:City walls|Benin]]\n[[Category:Walls]]\n[[Category:African architecture]]\n[[Category:Fortifications in Africa]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric Africa]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Historic buildings and structures in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Linear earthworks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n;Sources \n*{{cite journal| last=Igbafe | first=Philip A.| year=1970 | title=The fall of Benin: a reassessment | journal= Journal of African History | volume=11 | issue=3 |pages=385\u2013400 | doi=10.1017/S0021853700010215 | jstor=180345 | ref=harv }}\n* European traders in Benin to Major Copland Crawford. Reporting the stoppage of trade by the Benin King 1896 Apr 13, ''Catalogue of the Correspondence and Papers of the Niger Coast Protectorate'', 268 3/3/3, p.&nbsp;240. National Archives of Nigeria Enugu.\n* Sir Ralph Moore to Foreign Office. Reporting on the abortive Expedition into Benin. 1895 Sept.12 ''Catalogue of the Correspondence and Papers of the Niger Coast Protectorate'', 268 3/3/3, p.&nbsp;240. [[National Archives of Nigeria]] Enugu\n* J.R. Phillips to Foreign Office. Advising the deposition of the Benin King. 17 Nov 18